{"title_page": "London Fire Brigade", "text_new": "{{Redirect|LFB}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox fire department\n| name               = London Fire Brigade\n| logo               = London Fire Brigade Logo.png\n| motto              =\n<!-- Operational Area -->\n| country            = United Kingdom \n| subdivision_type1  = City\n| subdivision_type2  =\n| subdivision_type3  =\n| subdivision_name1  = [[London]]\n| subdivision_name2  =\n| subdivision_name3  =\n| address            = Union Street, {{postcode|SE|1}}\n| coordinates        =\n<!-- Agency Overview -->\n| established        = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1865}}\n| annual calls       = <!-- Include {{small|(1234)}} to indicate year of data -->\n| employees          = 5,992\n| annual budget      = \u00a3389.2 million<ref>http://moderngov.london-fire.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=2909</ref>\n| staffing           =\n| chief              = \n| captain            =\n| ALSorBLS           = <!-- [[advanced life support|ALS]] and/or [[basic life support|BLS]] -->\n<!-- Facilities & Equipment -->\n| reference1         = <ref name=\"LFB\" />\n| commissioner       =[[Andy Roe]] <ref name=\"Cotton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/first-woman-takes-over-at-london-fire-brigade-as-chief-retires-after-almost-a-decade-a3425826.html|title=First woman takes over at London Fire Brigade as chief retires after almost a decade|publisher=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=30 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230232639/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/first-woman-takes-over-at-london-fire-brigade-as-chief-retires-after-almost-a-decade-a3425826.html|archivedate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n| divisions          = 5\n| stations           = 103\n|  DPLs           = 47\n|  Pumps           = 55\n|  Pump-Ladders   = 55\n| FRU             = 15\n| TLs    = 4\n|  HPs           = 4\n|  ALPs          = 11 \n| USAR               = 14\n| Fire Boats = 2        \n\n<!-- Footer -->\n| reference2         = <ref name=\"LFB\" />\n| website            = {{Official website|http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/}}\n}}\n<!--Do not edit or change the number of fire stations without first referring to/discussing on the article's talk page-->\nThe '''London Fire Brigade''' ('''LFB''') is the [[statute|statutory]] [[Fire department|fire and rescue service]] for [[London]]. It was formed by the Metropolitan Fire Brigade Act 1865, under the leadership of superintendent [[Eyre Massey Shaw]].\n\nThe LFB is the busiest of all the [[fire services in the United Kingdom]]. It is the second largest in size, after the national [[Scottish Fire and Rescue Service]], and has the largest number of full-time firefighters. It has 5,992&nbsp;staff, including 5,096 operational [[firefighter]]s and officers based at 102 [[fire station]]s (plus one river station).<ref name=\"LFB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WhoWeAre.asp|title=Who we are|publisher=London Fire Brigade|accessdate=9 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429034538/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WhoWeAre.asp|archivedate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who we are|url=http://www.firescotland.gov.uk/about-us/whoweare.aspx|publisher=Scottish Fire and Rescue Service|accessdate=22 June 2014|quote=any of our 8,000 firefighters|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103211706/http://www.firescotland.gov.uk/about-us/whoweare.aspx|archivedate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe LFB is led by the Commissioner for Fire and Emergency Planning, Andy Roe. The brigade and Commissioner are overseen by the [[Greater London Authority]], which in April 2018 took over these responsibilities from the [[London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority]] (LFEPA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about-us/governance-london-fire-commissioner/|title=Governance - London Fire Commissioner|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2015-16 financial year the LFB received 171,488 emergency calls. These consisted of: 20,773 fires, 48,696 false alarms of fire and 30,066 other calls for service.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2015-16.pdf|title=LFEPA|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611020709/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2015-16.pdf|archivedate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"data.london.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/london-fire-brigade---whole-of-service-incident-summary-report-by-financial-year |title=Archived copy |accessdate=5 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206105337/https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/london-fire-brigade---whole-of-service-incident-summary-report-by-financial-year |archivedate=6 February 2017  }}</ref> As well as [[firefighting]], the LFB also responds to road [[traffic collision]]s, [[flood]]s, trapped-in-[[elevator|lift]] releases, and other incidents such as those involving [[Dangerous goods|hazardous materials]] or major transport accidents. It also conducts [[Emergency preparedness|emergency planning]] and performs [[fire safety]] inspections and education. It does not provide an [[ambulance]] service as this function is performed by the [[London Ambulance Service]] as an independent [[NHS trust]], although all LFB firefighters are trained in first aid and all of [[London Fire Brigade appliances|its fire engine]]s carry first aid equipment. Since 2016, the LFB has provided first aid for some life-threatening medical emergencies (e.g. cardiac or respiratory arrest).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_brigade-and-london-ambulance-service-team-up-for-life-saving-trial.asp#.WIpXBH2DEfI|title=News|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813185751/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_brigade-and-london-ambulance-service-team-up-for-life-saving-trial.asp#.WIpXBH2DEfI|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:DV307 no.50 The great fire, London June 23 1861 at 2.30am from Billingsgate.png|thumb|The 1861 Tooley Street fire from Billingsgate]]\nFollowing a multitude of ad-hoc firefighting arrangements and the [[Great Fire of London]], various insurance companies established firefighting units to tackle fires that occurred in buildings that their respective companies insured. As demands grew on the primitive firefighting units they began to coordinate and co-operate with each other until, on 1 January 1833, the London Fire Engine Establishment was formed under the leadership of [[James Braidwood (firefighter)|James Braidwood]], who had founded the first professional, municipal fire brigade in [[Edinburgh]].<ref name=LFBHist>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade: Key dates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> He introduced a uniform that, for the first time, included personal protection from the hazards of firefighting. With 80 [[firefighter]]s and 13 [[fire station]]s, the unit was still a private enterprise, funded by the insurance companies and as such was responsible mainly for saving material goods from fire.\n\nSeveral large fires, most notably at the [[Palace of Westminster]] in 1834<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade | History, key dates (Our history)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> and the [[1861 Tooley Street fire]] (in which Braidwood died in action, aged 61),<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /><ref>[[Tooley Street#Tooley Street fire, 1861|Tooley Street Fire]]</ref> spurred the insurance companies to lobby the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] to provide the brigade at public expense and management. After due consideration, in 1865 the Metropolitan Fire Brigade Act was passed,<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> creating the Metropolitan Fire Brigade under the leadership of [[Eyre Massey Shaw]], a former head of police and fire services in [[Belfast]]. In 1904 it was renamed as the London Fire Brigade.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> The LFB moved into a new headquarters built by [[Higgs and Hill]]<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49753 General introduction', Survey of London: volume 26: Lambeth: Southern area (1956), pp. 1\u201317.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605014439/http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49753 |date=5 June 2011 }} Date accessed: 27 March 2010.</ref> on the [[Albert Embankment]] in Lambeth in 1937, where it remained until 2007.<ref name=geo>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/832436|title=Lambeth: London Fire Brigade... (C) Nigel Cox :: Geograph Britain and Ireland|author=Nigel Cox|work=geograph.org.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012150842/http://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/832436|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:South London warehouse fire 1980.jpg|thumb|right|LFB firefighters at a warehouse in south London after a major fire in 1980]]\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]] the country's brigades were amalgamated into a single [[National Fire Service]]. The separate London Fire Brigade for the [[County of London]] was re-established in 1948.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> With the formation of [[Greater London]] in 1965, this absorbed most of the Middlesex Fire Brigade, the borough brigades for [[County Borough of West Ham|West Ham]], [[County Borough of East Ham|East Ham]] and [[County Borough of Croydon|Croydon]] and parts of the [[Essex County Fire and Rescue Service|Essex]], [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service|Hertfordshire]], [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service|Surrey]] and [[Kent Fire and Rescue Service|Kent]] brigades.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" />\n\nIn 1986 the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) was disbanded and a new [[statutory authority]], the [[London Fire and Civil Defence Authority]] (LFCDA), was formed to take responsibility for the LFB.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> The LFCDA was replaced in 2000 by the London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/FireAuthority.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101004173458/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/FireAuthority.asp|archivedate=4 October 2010}}</ref> At the same time, the [[Greater London Authority]] (GLA) was established to administer the LFEPA and coordinate emergency planning for London. Consisting of the [[Mayor of London]] and other elected members, the GLA also takes responsibility for the [[Metropolitan Police Service]], [[Transport for London]] and other functions.\n\nIn 2007 the LFB vacated its Lambeth headquarters and moved to a site in Union Street, [[Southwark]]. In the same year, the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] announced that LFB Commissioner [[Ken Knight]] had been appointed as the first [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Fire Services|Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser]] to the government.<ref>Communities and Local Government News Release 099, 24 May 2007, New Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser Appointed</ref> Knight was succeeded as Commissioner at that time by [[Ron Dobson]], who served for almost ten years. Dany Cotton took over in 2017, becoming the brigade's first female commissioner.<ref name=\"Cotton\" />\n\n=== Commissioners and chief officers ===\nAs of 1 January 2020 Andy Roe is the commissioner of the LFB. He succeeds [[Dany Cotton]], who in 2017 had become the first woman to hold the top role; Cotton resigned in the wake of the [[Grenfell Tower fire]] after 32 years' service in the brigade. Prior to Cotton, [[Ron Dobson]] was the commissioner and he had served in the LFB since 1979; he was awarded a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for his distinguished contribution to the fire service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_PR1543.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061616/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_PR1543.asp |archivedate=11 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* 1833 to 1861: [[James Braidwood (firefighter)|James Braidwood]] (director of the London Fire Engine Establishment, [[1861 Tooley Street fire|died in action]])<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade: key dates, (accessed 23 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref>\n* 1861 to 1891: [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Capt.]] [[Eyre Massey Shaw]] (superintendent, later chief officer)\n* 1891 to 1896: James Sexton Simmonds\n* 1896 to 1903: [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Capt.]] Lionel de Latour Wells\n* 1903 to 1909: [[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)|RAdm.]] James de Courcy Hamilton\n* 1909 to 1918: [[Lieutenant commander|Lt. Cdr.]] Sir Sampson Sladen\n* 1918 to 1933: Arthur Reginald Dyer, KPM<ref>Royal Warrant</ref>\n* 1933 to 1938: [[Major (United Kingdom)|Maj.]] Cyril Morris, MC<ref>http://www.thegazette.co.uk/all-notices/content/100068</ref>\n* 1938 to 1941: [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Cdr.]] Sir [[Aylmer Firebrace]], CBE\n* 1939 to 1941: Maj. Frank Jackson, CBE\n* ''1941 to 1948: [[National Fire Service|all fire brigades nationalised]]''\n* 1948 to 1962: Sir [[Frederick Delve]], CBE\n* 1962 to 1970: [[Leslie Leete]], CBE\n* 1970 to 1976: [[Joseph Milner (firefighter)|Joseph Milner]]\n* 1976 to 1980: Peter Darby\n* 1980 to 1987: Ronald Bullers\n* 1987 to 1991: Gerald Clarkson\n* 1991 to 2003: Brian Robinson, CBE (first commissioner)\n* 2003 to 2007: Sir [[Ken Knight]], CBE\n* 2007 to 2016: [[Ron Dobson]], CBE\n* 2017 to 2019: [[Dany Cotton]]\n* 2020 to present: Andy Roe\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:LFB Headquarters.JPG|thumb|London Fire Brigade headquarters from 1937 to 2007, in [[Lambeth]].]]\n[[File:London Fire Brigade HQ.jpg|thumb|The LFB's current headquarters since 2007, in [[Southwark]].]]\nHistorically, the London Fire Brigade was organised into two divisions: Northern and Southern, divided in most places by the [[River Thames]] and each commanded by a Divisional Officer. Both divisions were divided into three districts, each under a Superintendent with his headquarters at a \"superintendent station\". The superintendent stations themselves were commanded by District Officers, with the other stations under Station Officers.<ref name=\"info\">London Fire Brigade, ''The London Fire Brigade: Information for Intending Candidates'', December 1938.</ref>\n\nOn the creation of the [[Greater London Council]] in 1965, the brigade was enlarged and took over almost all of the Middlesex Fire Brigade, part of west Kent, North Surrey and South West Essex, together with the small County Borough brigades of Croydon, East Ham and West Ham.\n\nThe internal LFB organisation consists of three directorates that all report to the Commissioner. They are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/SeniorManagementTeam.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822095316/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/SeniorManagementTeam.asp|archivedate=22 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n* Operations;\n* Safety and Assurance;\n* Finance and Contractual Services.\n\nThe LFB's headquarters since 2007 is located in Union Street in [[Southwark]], adjacent to the brigade's training centre, which is both the original headquarters of the Massey Shaw fire brigade and his home, Winchester House, as well as the [[London Fire Brigade Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LFBHeadquarters.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925040029/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LFBHeadquarters.asp|archivedate=25 September 2010|access-date=4 October 2010}}</ref> The brigade was previously headquartered in [[Lambeth]] between 1937 and 2007.\n\n== Legislative powers ==\nFire and rescue authorities in England come under the government department formerly known as the Office of the Deputy Prime Minister (ODPM).  This department was responsible for legislation covering fire authorities; however, in 2006, a structural change to central government led to the  creation of the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] (DCLG).  It is now responsible for fire and resilience in England, including London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/|title=Fire prevention and rescue|work=communities.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318152355/http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/|archivedate=18 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004]] changed many working practices;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents|title=Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004|work=legislation.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916025154/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents|archivedate=16 September 2015}}</ref> it was brought in to replace the [[Fire Services Act 1947]] and repealed several existing acts, many going back fifty years. The full list of acts repealed can be found here:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents#sch2|title=Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004|work=legislation.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916025154/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents#sch2|archivedate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004 Act was drafted in response to the Independent Review of the Fire Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irfs.org.uk/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928110005/http://www.irfs.org.uk/|title=irfs.org.uk|archivedate=28 September 2007|work=irfs.org.uk}}</ref> often referred to as the Bain Report, after its author [[George Bain (academic)|Professor Sir George Bain]].  It recommended radical changes to many working procedures and led to a [[UK firefighter dispute 2002\u20132003|national firefighter strike in 2002\u20132003]].\n\nFurther changes to the legislative, organisational and structural fabric of the brigade, which could include varying the attendance time, the location of frontline appliances and number of personnel, plus mandatory performance targets, priorities and objectives are set by the DCLG in the form of a document called the Fire and Rescue Service National Framework. The framework is set annually by the government and applies to all brigades in England. Responsibility for the rest of the UK fire service is devolved to the various parliaments and assemblies. On country-wide issues, the [[Chief Fire Officers Association]] provides the collective voice on fire, rescue and resilience issues.<ref>[http://www.cfoa.org.uk/cfoa_public/ Chief Fire Officers Association] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821225957/http://www.cfoa.org.uk/cfoa_public/ |date=21 August 2006 }}</ref> Membership is made up from senior officers above the rank of Assistant Chief Officer, to Chief Fire Officer (or the new title of Brigade Manager).\n\n== Staffing ==\n\n=== Rank structure ===\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - London Fire Brigade with fire engine participating in the parade.png|alt=Two firefighters in red \"LFB PRIDE\" tshirts walk in a parade alongside a fire engine. The fire engine is decorated with at least five rainbow flags.|thumb|Staff of the London Fire Brigade as part of the Pride in London 2016 parade.]]\nThe London Fire Brigade, along with many UK fire and rescue services adopted a change in rank structure in 2006. The traditional ranks were replaced in the LFB, by new titles more descriptive to the job function.<ref>[http://www.ipds.co.uk/cd/fund.asp The Integrated Personal Development System (IPDS) (accessed 8 October 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007051312/http://www.ipds.co.uk/cd/fund.asp |date=7 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/rank_structure.asp London Fire Brigade: Rank structure] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904115633/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/rank_structure.asp |date=4 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2019, London Fire Brigade announced they are be returning to some of the old titles.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Current title || Rank markings\n|-\n|Firefighter ||  [[File:Capture FF insignia.jpg|80px]]\n|-\n|[[Leading Firefighter]] ||  [[File:Leading Firefighter.jpg|80px|]]\n|-\n|[[Sub-Officer]]|| [[File:Capture CM.JPG|80px]] \n|-\n|[[Station officer|Station Officer]]|| [[File:Capture WM.JPG|80px]] \n|-\n|Station Commander ||[[File:Capture SM.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Group Commander (also Borough Commander) ||[[File:Capture AM.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Deputy Assistant Commissioner||[[File:Capture daco.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n|Assistant Commissioner||[[File:Capture aco.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Deputy Commissioner ||[[File:Capture DCO.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n|Commissioner for Fire and Emergency Planning ||[[File:Capture co.JPG|80px]]\n|}\n\n=== Historical ranks ===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!1833\u20131938||1938\u20131965||1965\u20131992||1992\u20132001||2001\u20132003 || 2003-2019\n|-\n|Fireman 4th Class||Fireman||Fireman/Firewoman||colspan=3|Firefighter\n|-\n|Fireman 3rd Class||Senior Fireman||Leading Fireman/Firewoman||Leading Firefighter||Crew Commander (A)||N/A\n|-\n|Fireman 2nd Class||Sub-Officer||Sub-Officer||Sub-Officer||Crew Commander (B)<br />(or Watch Commander A [one-pump stations only])||Crew Manager\n|-\n|Fireman 1st Class||Station Officer||Station Officer||Station Officer||Watch Commander (B)||Watch Manager A/B\n|-\n|Junior Fireman||Assistant District Officer||Assistant Divisional Officer <br />(Station Commander from 1986)|| Assistant Divisional Officer<br />(or Station Commander)||colspan=2|Station Commander (or Deputy Group Commander)\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Senior Fireman||District Officer||Divisional Officer||Divisional Officer||colspan=2|Divisional Officer<br />(or Group Commander)\n|-\n|Senior District Officer||Deputy Assistant Chief Officer||colspan=3|Assistant Chief Officer (or Area Commander)\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Deputy Superintendent||rowspan=2|Deputy Chief Officer||Deputy Chief Fire Officer||rowspan=2 colspan=4|Deputy Chief Officer\n|-\n|Assistant Chief Fire Officer<br />(or Area Commander)\n|-\n|Superintendent||colspan=5|Chief Officer\n|}\n\n=== Recruitment and training ===\nIn the last 24 months the LFB have run 3 firefighter recruitment campaigns, however in previous years have seen fewer or even none. There are many factors as to why they would run a recruitment drive, as there is actually no set recruitment drive for firefighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/lfb_firefighter_recruitment#incoming-916441|title=LFB Firefighter Recruitment - a Freedom of Information request to London Fire Commissioner (London Fire Brigade)|date=4 December 2016|website=whatdotheyknow.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118043613/https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/lfb_firefighter_recruitment#incoming-916441|archivedate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\nProfessional firefighter training usually takes place at various London venues. On successful completion, the newly qualified firefighter is posted to a fire station to work on a shift pattern&nbsp;\u2013 currently two day shifts (ten and half hours), followed by two night shifts (thirteen and half hours), followed by four days off. Working patterns were the subject of scrutiny in Professor Bain's Independent Review of the Fire Service.<ref>[http://www.irfs.org.uk/atoz.htm Independent Review of the Fire Service, Prof Sir George Bain Pub: 16 Dec 2002] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001152517/http://www.irfs.org.uk/atoz.htm |date=1 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAfter training school, firefighters serve a one-year period of probation; qualification and full pay are not reached until the candidate completes a development folder which usually takes around 12\u201318 months. Ongoing training&nbsp;\u2013 both theoretical and practical&nbsp;\u2013 continues throughout the firefighter's career.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/recruitment/ff_training.asp London Fire Brigade: Training] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903085855/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/recruitment/ff_training.asp |date=3 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\n=== Shift pattern ===\nIn December 2010 the LFB and [[Fire Brigades Union]] (FBU) agreed on a new shift pattern for front-line firefighters: two 10\u00bd-hour day shifts then two 13\u00bd-hour night shifts followed by four days off.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12063474 | work=BBC News | title=London firefighters row over shift patterns resolved | date=22 December 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225170238/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12063474 | archivedate=25 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe agreement followed two 8-hour daytime [[Industrial action|strikes]] by the FBU<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1462.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Error Page<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029034734/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1462.asp |date=29 October 2010 }}</ref> in protest at the LFB's intention to change the shift pattern from two 9-hour day shifts then two 15-hour night shifts followed by three days off, to two 12-hour day shifts then two 12-hour night shifts followed by four days off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personneltoday.com/articles/2010/09/23/56604/firefighters-to-begin-industrial-action-in-dispute-over-shift.html|title=Firefighters to begin industrial action in dispute over shift patterns|work=Personnel Today|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924174037/http://www.personneltoday.com/articles/2010/09/23/56604/firefighters-to-begin-industrial-action-in-dispute-over-shift.html|archivedate=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nA London Fire Brigade report published in March 2012 stated that the shift changes have improved safety in the city. Compared with the 12 months prior to the shift changes, the 12 months following them saw firefighters able to spend more time on training, community safety work, and home safety visits (including the free fitting of smoke alarms).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_D034CCBEDCBB4498B9838A10FA89B43F.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323145935/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_D034CCBEDCBB4498B9838A10FA89B43F.asp |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Promotion ===\nIn order for a firefighter to gain promotion he or she must go through an assessment centre and reach the required standard set out by the Brigade. This process will be followed for each subsequent role the individual applies for, up to and including Assistant Commissioner. Appointments above the role of Assistant Commissioner are overseen by elected members of The London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/OurStaff.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323105551/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/OurStaff.asp|archivedate=23 March 2015|access-date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome promotion exams can be substituted by qualifications from the [[Institution of Fire Engineers]]. Firefighters and civilians such as building inspectors, scientists, surveyors and other practising professionals, take these qualifications either by written test or research.\n\nFuture promotion exams will be set using the Integrated Personal Development System (IPDS).<ref>[http://www.ipds.co.uk/public/site/newsdocs112/IPDS%20Booklet.pdf Integrated Personal Development System Booklet], (PDF download) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001185317/http://www.ipds.co.uk/public/site/newsdocs112/IPDS%20Booklet.pdf |date=1 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\n== Firefighting, special services and fire prevention ==\nIn 2010/11, the LFB handled a total of 212,657 emergency calls, including 5,241 [[prank call|hoax calls]] (although it only mobilised to 2,248 of those malicious false alarms). During the same period, it dealt with 13,367 major fires. There were 6,731 dwelling fires, including 748 that had been started deliberately; 73 people died in 58 fatal fires.\n\nIn addition to [[conflagration]]s, LFB firefighters respond to \"special services\".<ref name=\"frsa\">[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#7 Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004, published online the Office of Public Sector Information, (accessed 6 Nov 07)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190108/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#7 |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n[[File:LFB in action.jpg|thumb|right|LFB firefighters at a building fire; one uses an axe (right) to gain entry]]\n\nA special service is defined as every other non-fire related emergency, such as:<ref name=\"2010/11rpt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/Our_performance_2010-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 June 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105112459/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/Our_performance_2010-11.pdf |archivedate=5 January 2012  }}</ref>\n* [[Elevator|Lift]] releases (9,395 in 2010/11);\n* Effecting entry/exit (7,276 in 2010/11);\n* [[Flood]]ing (6,956 in 2010/11);\n* [[Traffic collision]]s (3,604 in 2010/11);\n* Spills and leaks (1,479 in 2010/11);\n* Assisting other agencies (855 in 2010/11);\n* \"Making safe\" operations (782 in 2010/11);\n* Animal rescues (583 in 2010/11);\n* Hazardous materials incidents (353 in 2010/11);\n* General evacuations (322 in 2010/11);\n* Suicides or attempts (229 in 2010/11); and\n* Waterborne rescues (38 in 2010/11).\n\nThe full scope of the brigade's duties and powers is enshrined in the Fire and Rescue Act 2004.\n\nFirefighters and, in some cases, specialist teams from the brigade's [[fire investigation]] unit, based at Dowgate, also investigate [[arson]] incidents, often working alongside the police and providing evidence in court. In 2008/09, deliberate fires accounted for 28% of all those attended by the LFB, a 28% reduction on the previous year.<ref name=\"london-fire.gov.uk\">{{cite web | url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2013-14.pdf | title=Our Performance 2013/2014 | accessdate=9 April 2015 | format=pdf | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005032701/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2013-14.pdf | archivedate=5 October 2015 | url-status=live | website=london-fire.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe other core duty of the brigade is to \"prevent damage\", and day-to-day fire prevention duties.\n\n=== Firefighting cover ===\n[[File:Sydenham substation fire.jpg|thumb|right|The LFB tackles a fire at an [[electrical substation]] in [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]].<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LastestIncidentsContainer_0B1355AE515C497D8CCEF7A1CE421B1A.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Upper Sydenham \u2013 electrical sub-station fire<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128060530/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LastestIncidentsContainer_0B1355AE515C497D8CCEF7A1CE421B1A.asp |date=28 November 2011 }}</ref>]]\nThe LFB provides fire cover according to a system of four risk categories which have traditionally been used across the UK, where every building is rated for its risk on a scale from \"A\" down to \"D\". The risk category determines the minimum number of appliances to be sent in a pre-determined mobilisation.\n\nCategory \"A\" includes areas with a high density of large buildings and/or population, such as offices or factories. Three fire engines are to arrive at \"A\" risks within eight minutes, the first two within five minutes.\n\nAreas with a medium density of large buildings and/or population, such as multi-storey residential blocks, will generally be classified \"B\" risk. Two fire engines will be deployed, with one to arrive within five minutes and the second within eight minutes.\n\nCategory \"C\" covers lower density, suburban areas and detached properties. One fire engine should arrive at a \"C\" risk incident within ten minutes. More rural areas not covered by the first three categories will be considered \"D\" risk. One fire engine should arrive at \"D\" risks within 20 minutes.\n\n=== Response times ===\n[[File:LFB dampening down after blaze.jpg|thumb|right|Damping down using an aerial ladder platform after a fire in Camden]]\nIn 2007/08, the first fire engine mobilised to a 999 call arrived within five minutes 58.8% of the time, and within eight minutes 90% of the time. The second fire engine deployed arrived within eight minutes 81.9% of the time, and within ten minutes 92.4% of the time.\n\nIn 2010/11, the average response time of the first appliance to the scene was 5 minutes 34 seconds (6 minute target), and the second appliance was 6 minutes 53 seconds (8 minute target).<ref name=\"2010/11rpt\" />\n\nIn 2015/16, the average response time for the first appliance to the scene was 5 minutes 33 seconds (6 minute target), and the second appliance to the scene was 6 minutes 55 seconds (8 minute target).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Mutual assistance ====\nThe Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004 gives the UK fire services the ability to call upon other services or fire authorities in what is known as mutual assistance.<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#13 Fire and Rescue Act 2004] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190108/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#13 |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> For example, the LFB played a comprehensive role in assisting [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]] at the [[Buncefield fire]] in 2005. Much earlier, the Hampton Court fire of 1986, which was on the border with Surrey, was attended by both the LFB and [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]].\n\nIn 2015/16 the LFB assisted at 567 \"over the border\" incidents.<ref name=\"data.london.gov.uk\"/>\n\nThe other fire services that adjoin the LFB are:\n* [[Essex County Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Kent Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Royal Berkshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Buckinghamshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n\nThe LFB also mobilises to support airport firefighters at [[London Heathrow Airport]], [[London City Airport]] and  The London Heliport.\n\n=== Determining the size of an incident ===\n[[File:Fire London 2011Dec.jpg|thumb|right|London Fire Brigade attending an incident in [[St Giles, London|St. Giles]] in December 2011.]]\n\nThe LFB, along with all other UK fire and rescue services, determines the size of a fire or special service by the final number of appliances mobilised to deal with it. For example, two appliances are despatched to a \"B\" risk area in response to a fire call in a residential house.  The officer-in-charge can request additional appliances by transmitting a radio message such as, \"make pumps 4\", or if persons are believed to be involved or trapped, \"make pumps 4, persons reported\".<ref>[http://www.shropshirefire.gov.uk/Docs/BrigadeOrders/Operations/Operations%20No%203%20Part%202%20-%20Incident%20Command%20Radio%20Messages%20-%20Main%20Radio%20Scheme.pdf Shropshire Fire and Rescue Service, Operational Note 3 (in the public domain, accessed 22 May 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630153210/http://www.shropshirefire.gov.uk/Docs/BrigadeOrders/Operations/Operations%20No%203%20Part%202%20-%20Incident%20Command%20Radio%20Messages%20-%20Main%20Radio%20Scheme.pdf |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref> The control room will then deploy a further two appliances making a total of four. Informally, firefighters refer to such fires as 'a make up' or 'a 4-pumper';\n<ref name=\"wallington\">Fireman! A Personal Account, by Neil Wallington, Pub David & Charles, 22 February 1979, {{ISBN|0-7153-7723-X}}</ref> when the fire is out, if no other pumping appliances were despatched, this would be recorded as a '4-pump fire'.\n\nIf an incident is more serious, it can be escalated straight to a 6-, 8- or 10-pump fire and beyond \u2013 in London this is usually completed in even numbers, though it is not uncommon for a 10-pump fire to be 'made up' to 15 if necessary.  A call to, say, a large warehouse ablaze could be escalated straight to a 10-pump fire. The 2007 [[Cutty Sark]] fire required 8 pumps;<ref name=\"press\">[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/latest_incidents.asp London Fire Brigade: Latest information on incidents in London, 21 May 2007 (accessed 22 May 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527000351/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/latest_incidents.asp |date=27 May 2007 }}</ref> as a serious incident escalates, the brigade deploys senior officers, Command Units and any specialist appliances required.\n\nExamples of 25-pump fires include the blaze at [[Alexandra Palace]] in 1980,<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=475 London Fire Brigade press release pr149/02 24 September 2002 (accessed 22 May 07)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021339/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=475 |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> and at the [[The Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust|Royal Marsden Hospital, Chelsea]] in 2008, the latter also involving four aerial appliances. The [[King's Cross fire]] in 1987 was a 30-pump fire,<ref>[http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/DoT_KX1987.pdf Dept of Transport, Investigation into the King's Cross fire: Desmond Fennell OBE, QC, Nov 1988 (accessed 25 October 2007)]</ref> as was the blaze in numerous shops on [[Oxford Street]] in April 2007. The [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in June 2017 was a 40-pump fire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/17/london-fire-brigade-dany-cotton-grenfell-tower|title=London fire brigade boss: \u2018It was a massive risk, but it\u2019s our job to go in\u2019|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617204103/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/17/london-fire-brigade-dany-cotton-grenfell-tower|archivedate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPumping appliances can only operate with a minimum crew of four, and a maximum of six (although this is rare) so it is possible to estimate the number of firefighters attending an incident by multiplying the number of pumps by five. For example, the Cutty Sark fire was described as \"an 8-pump fire attended by 40 firefighters\".<ref name=\"press\" />\n\n=== Special services ===\nCore services are paid for by London's [[Council Tax|council tax]] payers and through central government funding known as a grant settlement; each council tax payer's bill will include a precept \u2013 a specific part of their bill that contributes to the funding of the fire brigade. Those in need of the LFB's services in an emergency do not pay, but the brigade can provide additional special services for which it may charge where there is no immediate threat to life or imminent risk of injury.\n\nExamples of these special services which may be charged for include the clearing of flooded commercial premises, the use of brigade equipment for supplying or removing water, and making structures safe in cases where there is no risk of personal injury to the public.\n\n=== Safety and fire prevention ===\nLFB firefighters and watch officers often visit residential and commercial premises to advise on hazard risk assessment and fire prevention. They also provide safety education to schools and youth groups.  Each of the London boroughs has a central fire safety office that collates and coordinates fire prevention work in accordance with legislation, and they are supported by a dedicated team of specialist officers.\n\nIn 2010/11, the LFB made 70,016 home fire safety visits. Over 100,000 children are seen each year by the brigade's schools team. Around half of all serious fires occur in the home, and many house fires attended by the LFB no smoke alarm was fitted, despite the LFB fitting tens of thousands in homes every year.\n\n== Stations and equipment ==\n[[File:LFBstn.jpg|thumb|right|[[Dowgate]] fire station in the [[City of London]] is home to the [[fire investigation]] team]]\n[[File:Romford fire station.JPG|thumb|right|[[Romford]] fire station]]\nAs of 2014, the LFB has 103 fire stations, including one river station, across the 32 [[London borough]]s and the [[City of London]].<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_organisation.asp London Fire Brigade: Our Organisation (accessed 16 Jan 07)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208103552/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_organisation.asp |date=8 February 2007 }}</ref> They are staffed 24 hours a day by full-time employees of the brigade, and are linked to a control centre in [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/0DA45C1B1DC14505A4FA14A3D18EFBA0_PR2939.asp#.VZvvdBtVhBc|title=London Fire Brigade|date=1 February 2012|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708032706/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/0DA45C1B1DC14505A4FA14A3D18EFBA0_PR2939.asp#.VZvvdBtVhBc|archivedate=8 July 2015}}</ref> This centre was opened in 2012; calls to it are fed from 999 operators at [[BT Group|BT]], [[Cable & Wireless Worldwide|Cable & Wireless]] and [[Global Crossing]].\n\nCentral London stations can attend up to 8,000 calls per year, inner-city stations about 3,000 to 4,000 calls per year (these tend to be the stations that are busy serving the densely populated areas), and outlying or suburban fire stations may attend around 1,500 calls which include road traffic accidents, grass fires and house fires.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/az/az_stations.asp London Fire Brigade: A-Z of fire stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212090045/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/az/az_stations.asp |date=12 December 2004 }}</ref>\n\nSome UK fire authorities use retained (part-time) firefighters who live and work near their local station and are on-call, but the LFB is one of only three UK fire services where all operational staff are full-time employees.\n\nEach station has four shifts, or 'watches': red, white, blue and green, with a Watch Manager in charge of each. The overall management of the station falls to the Station Manager, who will also attend serious incidents, as well as spending time on call.\n\nA group of one (City of London) to five (Tower Hamlets) stations within a borough are managed by a Borough Commander (Group Commander) who interacts strategically on a local level with the Borough Commander for the police and ambulance services and the chief executive of the local authority.\n\n=== Stations and districts ===\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/A-ZFireStations.asp Alphabetical fire station listing and addresses from the London Fire Brigade website]\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/150/map-of-london-fire-stations.asp Interactive map of current (status: 2016) and former London Fire Brigade fire stations]\n\nUpon the founding of the London County Council in 1965, the new authority was organised into 11 divisions, of roughly 10 to 12 stations each, designated 'A' Division through to 'L' Division, dispatched by three 999 mobilising control rooms. 'A' (West End), 'D' (West London), 'G' (North West London) and 'J' (North London) mobilised from Wembley (the former Middlesex headquarters); 'B' (Central London south of the river), 'E' (South East London and Kent), 'H' (South London and Surrey) and 'K' (South West London south of the river and Surrey) mobilised from Croydon (the former Croydon County Borough headquarters); finally, 'C' (City and Inner East London), 'F' (East London including Docklands) and 'L' (North East London and South West Essex), mobilised from Stratford (the former West Ham County Borough headquarters). Each of these divisions were, to a degree, autonomous of each other and had their own divisional management hierarchy. This arrangement lasted until 1989 when the brigade was re-organised into the current arrangement.\n\nThe LFB is currently formed into five divisions: Northern, Eastern, Western, Southeastern and Southwestern. As of 2013, 21 fire stations were located in the Northern Division and have [[call sign]]s prefixed \"A\"; 26 were in the Eastern Division with call signs prefixed \"F\"; Western Division consisted of 21 stations with \"G\"-prefixed call signs; 22 were under the Southeastern Division with an \"E\" prefix; and the remaining 22 were based in the Southwestern Division, call signs prefixed \"H\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2008/02/firemans-own-book-containing-accounts.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724160820/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2008/02/firemans-own-book-containing-accounts.html|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> As part of this organisation, many stations were re-coded.\n\nBelow is a complete listing, as of 2014, of the 102 fire stations of the London Fire Brigade according to district and station radio callsign. The LFB is divided into five districts, each designated by a letter of the alphabet: the Northern District Command is designated as \"A\"; the Southeastern District Command is designated as \"E\"; the Eastern District Command is designated as \"F\"; the Western District Command is designated as \"G\"; the Southwestern District Command is designated as \"H\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n;Northern District\nThe Northern District Command is designated as \"A\" or \"Alpha\". There are currently 17 fire stations in the Northern District. The Northern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[London Borough of Haringey|Haringey]], [[London Borough of Islington|Islington]], the [[City of Westminster]] and the [[City of London]].\n\n;Southeastern District\nThe Southeastern District Command is designated as \"E\" or \"Echo\". There are currently 19 fire stations in the Southeastern District. The Southeastern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[Bexley (London Borough)|Bexley]], [[Bromley (London Borough)|Bromley]], [[Greenwich (London Borough)|Greenwich]], [[Lewisham (London Borough)|Lewisham]], and [[Southwark (London Borough)|Southwark]].\n\n;Eastern District\nThe Eastern District Command is designated as \"F\" or \"Foxtrot\". There are currently 23 fire stations in the Eastern District. The Eastern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[Barking and Dagenham]], [[Hackney (London Borough)|Hackney]]\n, [[Havering (London Borough)|Havering]], [[Newham (London Borough)|Newham]], [[Redbridge (London Borough)|Redbridge]], [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], and [[Waltham Forest]].\n\n;Western District\nThe Western District Command is designated as \"G\" or \"Golf\". There are currently 21 fire stations in the Western District. The Western District serves the following boroughs of London: Brent, Ealing, Hammersmith and Fulham, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, and Kensington and Chelsea.\n\n;Southwestern District\nThe Southwestern District Command is designated as \"H\" or \"Hotel\". There are currently 22 fire stations in the Southwestern District, including the independent River Station, the quarters of the Fireboat. The Southwestern District serves the following boroughs of London: Croydon, Kingston upon Thames, Lambeth, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, and Wandsworth.\n\n=== Appliances ===\n{{Main|London Fire Brigade appliances}}\n[[File:1995 London Fire engine.jpg|thumb|right|A 1995-registered pump ladder appliance pictured in 2011 (no longer operational)]]\n[[File:LFB fireboat.JPG|thumb|right|''Fireflash'', registered in 1999, is one of London's two [[fireboat]]s]]\n[[File:One of the LFB's New Appliances.png|thumb|One of the LFB's newest appliances in 2016]]\n[[File:LFB Scania P410 64M Turntable Ladder.jpg|thumb|2020 Scania P410 64M Turntable Ladder]]\n[[File:LFB Scania L360 32M Turntable Ladder.jpg|thumb|2020 Scania L360 32M Turntable Ladder]]\n\nAll 102 LFB stations (not counting the river station) have a conventional [[Fire apparatus|fire appliance]] known as a dual pump ladder. Around 55 stations are also assigned one additional pump. Numerous other stations are home to a range of other specialist vehicles.\n\nThe stations that are assigned both a dual pump ladder and a pump are generally the busier stations receiving over 2,000 emergency calls (known colloquially by firefighters as \"shouts\") per year. They may also be stations of strategic importance, or those located in areas considered to be high risk. The remaining stations equipped with a single pump ladder generally attend fewer than 2,000 calls per year.\n\nAn earlier fleet of mostly [[Volvo]] vehicles was phased out, with some retained for training and reserve purposes, and replaced between 2002 and 2011 with new [[Mercedes-Benz]] vehicles.\n\nIn 2012, the LFB purchased five [[Mini Countryman]]s for conversion into instant response vehicles. The two-seat cars are fitted with six extinguishers (two each of water, foam and powder), plus a first-aid kit and defibrillator, and may be deployed to investigate automatic alarms actuating and smaller fires such as those in rubbish bins which do not require a full-sized engine and crew. The brigade has indicated a wish to add more smaller vehicles to its fleet, including [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover utility vehicles]] which could be fitted with water pumps, breathing apparatus and pull-out equipment drawers, and with enough space for four firefighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/ingear/cars/article1218397.ece|title=Little squirts to the rescue&nbsp;\u2013 The Sunday Times|work=thesundaytimes.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221083538/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/ingear/cars/article1218397.ece|archivedate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the LFB announced they would be replacing the older-generation (currently used) [[Mercedes-Benz Atego]] pump appliances with brand new Mercedes-Benz Ategos which include new features such as: an improved 'crew cab' for the comfort and safety of firefighters, new high-pressure hoses which can deliver twice as much water as previous models, a brand new electronically-controlled pump, and a more economical and environment-friendly EURO VI engine, which will be compatible with London's low-emission zones. In 2017, 52 initial appliance orders are being rolled out across London ready for operational use, replacing the older 2002-2004 pumps, and later replacing the newer 2006-2008 pumps. The primary reason for the replacement of the older Ategos was due to their age (some being 15 years old) and poor economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_New-Brigade-vehicle-prototype-gets-royal-approval.asp#.WH582H2DHIU|title=News|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101113950/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_New-Brigade-vehicle-prototype-gets-royal-approval.asp#.WH582H2DHIU|archivedate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the LFB's frontline operational fleet consists of:\n* Approximately 100 Dual Pump Ladders (DPL) (plus approximately 25 used for training)\n* Approximately 50 Pumps (P)\n* 15 Fire Rescue Units (FRU) (plus 1 for training)\n* 14 [[Urban Search and Rescue]] (USAR) multi-purpose vehicles\n* 8 Incident Response Units (IRU)\n* 8 Command Support Units (CSU)\n* 7 Aerial Ladder Platforms (ALP)\n* 6 Operational Support Units (OSU)\n* 6 High-volume Pumps (HVP)\n* 6 Fire Investigation Units (FIU)\n* 5 Instant Response Vehicles (IRV)\n* 4 Turntable Ladders (TL)\n* 4 Hose Laying Units (HLU)\n* 3 Bulk Foam Units (BFU)\n* 2 Scientific Support Units (SSU)\n* 2 Detection, Identification, and Monitoring Units (DIM)\n* 1 All-terrain Pump\n* 1 Heavy Distribution Unit (HDU)\n* 1 Fire Investigation Dog Unit (FID)\n* 1 Fireboat (plus 1 used as a reserve and for training)\n\n=== Improvements ===\nThe programme of improvements in staffing and equipment undertaken by the LFB since the [[September 11 attacks]] to improve London's resilience and its capability to deal with major emergencies, including the threat of terrorism has included: ten Incident Response Units; two Scientific Support Units; four different types of [[urban search and rescue]] (USAR) vehicles and ten USAR personnel carriers; three mass decontamination resilience units; and six equipment carriers known as Operational Support Units.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=893 Better preparation for major emergencies and terrorist attacks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010025037/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=893 |date=10 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nArchitecturally, fire stations vary in age and design from [[Edwardian era]] red-brick fire houses to modern spacious blocks complete with additional specialist facilities.<ref>[http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=20 Firefleet.co.uk gallery of London fire stations] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030939/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=20 |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> Early fire stations were originally built with horse-drawn appliances in mind and with traditional features such as the [[fireman's pole]], used by firefighters to gain rapid access from their upstairs quarters to the fire engine garages below when summoned.\n\nMore modern fire stations, though constructed without such features, often have more spacious accommodation and facilities for staff of both sexes, public visitor areas such as community safety offices and other amenities. An example of these is the new fire station in [[Hammersmith]] which opened in 2003,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2977963.stm New \u00a37.7m fire station at Hammersmith] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209213057/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2977963.stm |date=9 February 2008 }}, 2003</ref> just a few hundred yards along Shepherd's Bush Road from the previous local fire station which had been constructed in 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hammersmithtoday.co.uk/default.asp?section=info&page=oldfirestation.htm|title=Hammersmith Old Fire Station Set to be a Pub|work=hammersmithtoday.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929152752/http://www.hammersmithtoday.co.uk/default.asp?section=info&page=oldfirestation.htm|archivedate=29 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Modernisation ===\n\nIn 2008, existing LFB facilities were deemed unsuitable to meet the demands of modern firefighting and training. The LFB has been training firefighters at its current Grade 2 [[listed building]] in Southwark since 1878.<ref name=\"Training P.31\">\"LFB works with Babcock to deliver change to firefighter training\" ''Training''.  April/May 2012 MMC Publications. P.31</ref>\n\nIn response, the LFB signed a partnership contract with Babcock International Group PLC to provide firefighter training over the course of 25 years beginning in 2012.<ref name=\"Training P.31\" /> Babcock is also the number one training provider to the [[Royal Navy]], which includes firefighter training. The improvement program for firefighting training will introduce two new dedicated training centres and upgrades to 10 regional training centres. There will also be further improvements through additional computers and training facilities across many of the capital's 103 fire stations. The new firefighting training systems, supplied by [[Process Combustion Ltd]], will have low environmental impact and will allow firefighter training to take place at night under simulated extreme conditions that firefighters will face on incident ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.process-combustion.co.uk/firetraining/firetraining_overview.html |title=Fire Training Systems \u2013 Bespoke Fire Training System |work=Process Combustion |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712013452/http://www.process-combustion.co.uk/firetraining/firetraining_overview.html |archivedate=12 July 2012 }}</ref> In addition to improving training facilities, Babcock's proposals will increase the amount of time available for firefighter training and save the LFB an estimated \u00a366m over the next 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babcockinternational.com/media-centre/babcock-selected-as-preferred-bidder-for-london-fire-brigade-training/?alttemplate=MobileNewsItem |title=London Fire Brigade chooses Babcock to deliver biggest changes to firefighting training for 130 years |work=babcockinternational.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729024416/http://www.babcockinternational.com/media-centre/babcock-selected-as-preferred-bidder-for-london-fire-brigade-training/?alttemplate=MobileNewsItem |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n=== Fire station closures ===\n[[File:This fire station is now closed - Clerkenwell.jpg|thumb|Sign in the window of Clerkenwell fire station reads \"This fire station is now closed\".]]\nThe creation of the Greater London Council in 1965 saw the number of LFB stations increase. The LFB absorbed some stations from the county brigades. At the time there were a handful of smaller brigades: Middlesex, Croydon, West Ham and East Ham \u2013 they were all incorporated into the LFB.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade Key Dates (1965), (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> By 1965 the LFB had 115 stations, plus two river stations.\n\nThe LFB has an ongoing policy of upgrading existing fire stations, and building new stations to replace those that are no longer suitable for the requirements of a modern-day fire service.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=793 LFB Press Release P039/06, 23 June 06, (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012062149/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=793 |date=12 October 2007 }}</ref> In February 2010, [[Boris Johnson]] officially opened the LFB's first new station in four years, at [[Harold Hill]]. The mayor hailed the station's exceptional environmental sustainability, calling it the \"greenest station in the capital\".<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1303.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Error Page<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006204951/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1303.asp |date=6 October 2010 }}</ref> In the past two decades the total number of stations has reduced slightly, with the following permanent closures, including 10 in January 2014 as part of budget cuts:\n* 2014: [[Belsize Park|Belsize]] (A42), [[Bow, London|Bow]] (F27), [[Clerkenwell]] (A27), [[Downham]] (E32), [[Dalston|Kingsland]] (F31), [[Knightsbridge]] (A26), [[Silvertown]] (F46), [[Southwark]] (E33), [[Westminster]] (A25), and [[Woolwich]] (E24).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london24.com/news/protests_at_london_fire_stations_over_closures_as_union_says_boris_johnson_has_blood_on_his_hands_1_3188492 |title=Protests at London fire stations over closures as union says Boris Johnson has \u2018blood on his hands\u2019 |work=London 24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109203045/http://www.london24.com/news/protests_at_london_fire_stations_over_closures_as_union_says_boris_johnson_has_blood_on_his_hands_1_3188492 |archivedate=9 January 2014 }}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Manchester Square]] (A22)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=157|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=157|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Manchester Square 1889 color fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1999: [[Barbican Estate|Barbican]] (A29)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=4|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=4|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Barbican fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1998: Heathrow Airport (new station subsequently opened when the central terminal area was re-classified as \"A\" risk)<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/lfepa/reports/2005/fep778.pdf Heathrow Fire Station \u2013 Taking of new lease 15 Sep 05 (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025155514/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/lfepa/reports/2005/fep778.pdf |date=25 October 2007 }}</ref>\n* 1998: [[Shooter's Hill]] (E26)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=218|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=218|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Shooters Hill 1912 fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1993: [[Sanderstead]] (H30) (originally a Surrey Fire Brigade station)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=210|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=210|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Sanderstead 1935 fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Regional control centre ==\n{{Main|FiReControl}}\nIn October 2007, the Department for Communities and Local Government announced that the location for the new regional control centre, dedicated to the capital and part of the [[FiReControl]] project, would be at the Merton industrial estate in the [[London Borough of Merton]].<ref>Dept of Communities and Local Government: News Release 193, Site of  London's New Fire Control Centre Announced, 17 October 2007</ref> FiReControl was however scrapped in 2010.\n\n== Major or notable incidents ==\nThe geographical area covered by the LFB along with the major transport infrastructure and the political, business and administrative bases typical of a capital city has seen the brigade involved in many significant incidents.\n\n=== Major incident procedure ===\nA \"major incident\" is defined as any emergency that requires the implementation of special arrangements by one or more of London's emergency services and will generally include the involvement, either directly or indirectly, of large numbers of people.<ref name=MetMajorIncident>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.police.uk/leslp/docs/Major_incident_procedure_manual_7th_ed.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111182638/http://www.met.police.uk/leslp/docs/Major_incident_procedure_manual_7th_ed.pdf |archivedate=11 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAny member of any of the emergency services can initiate a major incident. Responsibility for the rescue of persons involved lies with the LFB. The care and transportation of casualties to hospital is the responsibility of the London Ambulance Service. Police will ease these operations by co-ordinating the emergency services, local authorities and other agencies.<ref name=MetMajorIncident />\n\nWhen a major incident is declared the services, along with civilian agencies, use a structural system known as [[Gold \u2013 silver \u2013 bronze command structure|gold-silver-bronze command]] that allows them to follow a set procedure for incident management.  Put simply, gold relates to strategic control of an incident, silver to tactical command, and bronze to operational control.  The term gold command can also relate to an emergency service building, mobile control unit or other base that becomes the focal point (often remotely) for the incident's management.<ref name=MetMajorIncident />\n\nAdditionally, a major incident can lead to the government activating its coordination facility, known as [[Cabinet Office Briefing Room|COBR]].\n\n=== Notable incidents ===\n<!-- This list is currently in descending chronological order. -->\nNotable incidents, some declared \"major incidents\" and some in which firefighters lost their lives, where the LFB has played a significant role include:\n* '''Grenfell Tower fire, 2017''' (40 pumps)\n[[File:Grenfell Tower fire.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in 2017]]\n: In June 2017 the LFB sent over 200 firefighters and officers in 40 fire engines, all 14 of its fire rescue units, four aerial ladder platforms and multiple command and operational support units to the [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in north Kensington. Crews were mobilised to the large tower block, which was ultimately almost completely alight, on the Lancaster West estate in the early hours of 14 June 2017 and some remained there for several days bringing the blaze under control. One of [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]]'s aerial ladder platforms was also requested due to its additional height. There were 72 fatalities making the incident Britain's deadliest residential fire since [[the Blitz]] during World War II.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_North-Kensington-tower-block-fire-Wednesday-14-June.asp|title=Incidents|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102183627/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_North-Kensington-tower-block-fire-Wednesday-14-June.asp|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Wembley industrial estate, 2017''' (20 pumps)\n: Over 120 firefighters, 20 pumps and four aerial ladder platforms were mobilised to a large fire in industrial units in Wembley in January 2017. The blaze affected a number of two-storey units and took around 17 hours to bring under control, and days to dampen down and declare the site safe. Crews from Wembley, Northolt, Willesden, Park Royal, Stanmore and Hillingdon fire stations attended the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_wembley-industrial-unit-fire.asp|title=Incidents|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531124922/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_wembley-industrial-unit-fire.asp|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Camden market fire, 2014''' (10 pumps)\n: Ten fire engines and over 70 firefighters and officers were called to a fire at Stables Market on Chalk Farm Road, [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], in May 2014. A number of shops under railway arches were damaged by the blaze. Around 600 people were evacuated from the area. Crews were first mobilised at around 8 p.m. and the fire was under control by 10:50 p.m. Crews from Kentish Town, Euston, West Hampstead, Lambeth, Holloway, Islington and Soho stations attended the incident. Early indications suggested that the cause of the fire was an accidental electrical issue.\n* '''Vauxhall helicopter crash, 2013'''\n:Nearly 150 firefighters were involved in operations following [[Vauxhall helicopter crash|a helicopter crash]] in [[Vauxhall]] in misty conditions during the morning rush-hour on 16 January 2013. Several specialist vehicles, including heavy rescue and urban search and rescue, were mobilised to the scene where the wreckage fell onto a street, damaging five cars, two motorbikes and two adjacent buildings, after the aircraft's rotor blades struck a [[Crane (machine)|construction crane]] attached to [[St George Wharf Tower]]. The pilot and one person on the ground were killed in the incident. Fire crews also attended the tower block where the crane was left in a precarious position, and evacuated hundreds of workers and dozens of homes. A [[fireboat]] also carried out a precautionary search of the nearby [[River Thames]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_16Jan12R.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|date=27 October 2011|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119022842/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_16Jan12R.asp|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-21049125 | publisher=BBC News | title=London helicopter crash: Pilot's death 'devastating' | date=16 January 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117040525/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-21049125 | archivedate=17 January 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Dagenham recycling centre fire, 2012''' (40 pumps)\n:Over 200 firefighters attended what was described by the commissioner as the largest fire in London \"for several years\". The LFB took just over four hours to bring under control the one-storey [[Dagenham]] recycling plant the size of a football pitch which was completely alight, sending a plume of smoke over east London. In addition to 40 fire engines, an aerial ladder platform, command unit, hose layer and three operational support vehicles attended.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19234182 | publisher=BBC News | title=Biggest fire 'for years' in Dagenham, London | date=12 August 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820000822/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19234182 | archivedate=20 August 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Camden Market fire, 2008''' (20 pumps)<ref name=journal>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2007/05/welcome.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052050/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2007/05/welcome.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n:Fire ravaged the stalls at the historic [[Camden Market]] in February 2008, forcing the evacuation of 450 people from the area, including 100 from their homes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1578257/Camden-Market-fire-damage-will-cost-millions.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Lewis | last=Carter | title=Camden Market fire damage 'will cost millions' | date=11 February 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914020436/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1578257/Camden-Market-fire-damage-will-cost-millions.html | archivedate=14 September 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Twenty fire engines and over 100 firefighters fought to bring the blaze under control within six hours and prevent any loss of life.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7237119.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Blaze ravages London market area | date=9 February 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215072250/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7237119.stm | archivedate=15 February 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Cutty Sark fire, 2007''' (6 pumps)\n:Although no lives were endangered and a major incident was not initiated, the fire at the historic tea clipper ''[[Cutty Sark]]'' in May 2007 became a notable incident for the widespread interest of national media and the unusual circumstances \u2013 having been caused by an industrial vacuum cleaner inadvertently left switched on by renovation workers for 48 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6675381.stm|title=BBC NEWS \u2013 UK \u2013 England \u2013 London \u2013 Blaze ravages historic Cutty Sark|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523120139/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6675381.stm|archivedate=23 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3109243/Cutty-Sark-fire-Security-guards-put-their-feet-up-as-blaze-ravaged-ship.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Edwards | title=Cutty Sark fire: Security guards 'put their feet up' as blaze ravaged ship | date=30 September 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201174318/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3109243/Cutty-Sark-fire-Security-guards-put-their-feet-up-as-blaze-ravaged-ship.html | archivedate=1 December 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Two fire appliances and an aerial appliance arrived at the scene within six minutes of the initial call to emergency services, and the commanding officer immediately requested an additional four appliances; firefighters brought the blaze under control within an hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/CuttySarkFireReport-29Sep08.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128063551/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/CuttySarkFireReport-29Sep08.pdf |archivedate=28 November 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''Oxford Street, 2007''' (30 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:From 27 to 28 April 2007 London's busiest shopping area was closed whilst more than 100 firefighters tackled a large fire in a flat above a department store on [[Oxford Street]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6597753.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Crews tackle Oxford Street fire | date=26 April 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901233125/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6597753.stm | archivedate=1 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The clothing retailer [[New Look (clothing retailer)|New Look]] was later fined a record \u00a3400,000 for fire safety breaches.<ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23775110-new-look-fined-pound-40000-after-oxford-street-fire.do New Look fined \u014140,000 after Oxford Street fire | News<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109134638/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23775110-new-look-fined-pound-40000-after-oxford-street-fire.do |date=9 January 2011 }}</ref>\n[[File:Buncefield015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Buncefield fire]]]]\n* '''Buncefield oil terminal, 2005'''\n:The UK's [[Buncefield fire|largest peacetime fire]] broke out on 11 December 2005 at the [[Hertfordshire Oil Storage Terminal]] at Buncefield. Although the major incident was attended by the LFB, its role was assisting and providing additional foam supplies to the neighbouring [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]], to the north of London, whose \"ground\" the incident took place in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/read_this/buncefield_explosions/|title=BBC \u2013 Beds Herts and Bucks \u2013 Read This \u2013 Depot explosion|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060715181824/http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/read_this/buncefield_explosions/|archivedate=15 July 2006}}</ref>\n* '''7 July 2005 bombings''' (12/12/10 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:Multiple major incidents were declared across London in response to the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|7/7 terrorist attacks]]. A total of 34 pumps and nine fire-rescue units were mobilised to the four bomb sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_4942000/4942238.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 7 \u2013 2005: Bomb attacks on London|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610231301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_4942000/4942238.stm|archivedate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n* '''Bethnal Green Road, 2004''' (8 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:A fire in shops and flats in Bethnal Green Road, [[Bethnal Green]] in July 2004 gained coverage in the national media due to the deaths of two LFB firefighters. The first LFB fatalities since 1993 were two of the 50 mobilised to the scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3909269.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Two firefighters killed in blaze | date=20 July 2004 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519023800/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3909269.stm | archivedate=19 May 2006 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Buckingham Palace fire, 2002''' (20 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:Fire broke out on 2 June 2002 in the west terrace of [[Buckingham Palace]]. At its peak, 20 fire engines and 100 firefighters were on the scene, and in the course of firefighting operations four people were rescued from the roof. The Royal Family were away at the time.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2022274.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Buckingham Palace blaze out | date=2 June 2002 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202132522/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2022274.stm | archivedate=2 February 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/jun/03/jubilee.monarchy2 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Rebecca | last1=Allison | first2=Tania | last2=Branigan | title=Thousands evacuated in fire | date=3 June 2002 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328011447/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/jun/03/jubilee.monarchy2 | archivedate=28 March 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Paddington train crash, 1999''' (12 pumps)\n:Also known as the [[Ladbroke Grove rail crash]], two trains collided a short distance outside of [[London Paddington station|Paddington station]] in October 1999, killing 31 people.<ref name=journal /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/5/newsid_2493000/2493593.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 5 \u2013 1999: Death toll rising in Paddington crash|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307125727/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/5/newsid_2493000/2493593.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Cannon Street train crash, 1991'''\n:Two people were killed and over 500 injured in the [[Cannon Street station rail crash]] in January 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 8 \u2013 1991: One dead as train crashes into buffers|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108160834/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|archivedate=8 January 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Marchioness disaster, 1989'''\n:The [[Marchioness disaster]] of August 1989 involved a collision on the [[River Thames]] between a pleasure boat, the ''Marchioness'', and a gravel dredger, the ''Bowbelle'', resulting in the sinking of the ''Marchioness'' and the deaths of 51 people. Initial confusion over which bridge the ship had sunk near meant fireboats and fire engines were sent in the wrong direction. It was not until half an hour later that a station officer from Southwark radioed: \"''Marchioness'' sunk, believed downstream of Blackfrairs Bridge with unknown number of people in river and Met Police searching river between Blackfriars and Waterloo Bridges.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/20/newsid_2500000/2500211.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 20 \u2013 1989: Marchioness river crash 'kills 30'|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307113723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/20/newsid_2500000/2500211.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Clapham Junction train crash, 1988'''\n:The [[Clapham Junction rail crash]] occurred on 12 December 1988 when a busy commuter train passed a defective signal and ran into the back of a second train, derailing it into the path of an oncoming third train. Thirty-five people died and 69 others suffered serious injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/12/newsid_2547000/2547561.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 12 \u2013 1988: 35 dead in Clapham rail collision|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307133743/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/12/newsid_2547000/2547561.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''King's Cross fire, 1987'''\n:The [[King's Cross fire]] broke out on 18 November 1987 under a wooden [[escalator]] leading from one of the [[King's Cross St. Pancras tube station|King's Cross tube station]] platforms to the surface. The blaze and smoke claimed 31 lives, including that of Soho station officer Colin Townsley while he rescued a woman from a ticket office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/kings-cross-fire-1987.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708051619/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/kings-cross-fire-1987.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref> Investigation and research of the fire resulted in the discovery of the [[trench effect]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_2519000/2519675.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 18 \u2013 1987: King's Cross station fire 'kills 27'|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070627175401/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_2519000/2519675.stm|archivedate=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n* '''Hampton Court fire, 1986''' (20 pumps, jointly with Surrey)\n: On 31 March 1986, a fire broke out at [[Hampton Court Palace]], which killed one person. 20 fire engines and around 125 firefighters from both the LFB and the neighbouring [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]] were sent to the scene, which is on the border between the two areas. Firefighters played a major role in the rescue of some of the more valuable artworks from the palace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/hampton-court-palace-blaze-recalled-11131124|title=Hampton Court Palace blaze recalled 30 years on after fire ripped through historic building|work=Get Surrey|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n* '''New Cross house fire, 1981'''\n:The infamous [[New Cross house fire]] of 18 January 1981 claimed the lives of 13 people, all aged between 14 and 22, attending a birthday party.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3479827.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Eyewitnesses describe killer fire | date=11 February 2004 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040227141935/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3479827.stm | archivedate=27 February 2004 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The exact and true cause has never been established.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12182927 | publisher=BBC News | title=Did the New Cross fire create a black British identity? | date=18 January 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121063429/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12182927 | archivedate=21 January 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Denmark Place fire, 1980'''\n:In the early hours of 15 August 1980, a man who was earlier ejected from an illegal drinking and gambling club in [[Soho]] returned with gasoline and started a fire that killed 37 people and injured 23 others. The incident became known as the [[Denmark Place fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2010/01/soho-club-fire-1980.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052202/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2010/01/soho-club-fire-1980.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''The Granary warehouse, 1978''' (35 pumps, 6 turntable ladders)\n:1 October 1978 saw one of London's largest post\u2013[[World War II]] fires, at The Granary warehouse on St. Pancras Way. At the first call at 2:58 a.m., three fire engines and a turntable ladder were sent to the scene. The scale of the blaze is evidenced by the rapid development of the LFB's mobilisation: make pumps four at 3:05 a.m.; make pumps six at 3:07 a.m.; make pumps 10 at 3:12 a.m.; make pumps 15 and turntable ladders 2 at 3:19 a.m.; make turntable ladders 4 at 3:39 a.m.; make pumps 20 and turntable ladders 6 at 3:51 a.m.; make pumps 25 at 4:19 a.m.; make hose layers 2 at 4:30 a.m.; and make pumps 35 at 5:13 a.m. At 4:50 a.m., the structure suffered a major collapse, killing firefighter Stephen Neill from Barbican station, seriously injuring three others, and destroying two fire engines.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Moorgate train crash, 1975'''\n:The [[Moorgate tube crash]] was a disaster on the London Underground in February 1975 when a train failed to stop and crashed into the [[Buffer stop|buffers]] at the end of a tunnel. The driver and 42 passengers were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/february/28/newsid_4298000/4298307.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 28 \u2013 1975: Horror underground|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620042156/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/february/28/newsid_4298000/4298307.stm|archivedate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Worsley Hotel fire, 1974''' (30 pumps)\n:The [[Worsley Hotel fire]] of December 1974 was an arson attack that killed seven people, including probationary firefighter Hamish Petit of Paddington station. Four fire engines, a turntable ladder and emergency tender were initially mobilised to the scene, gradually increased to 30 pumps with three turntable ladders, three emergency tenders, and hose layers. A 41-year-old kitchen porter was convicted of the attack and seven counts of manslaughter and was jailed for life.<ref name=journal /><ref name=LineOfDuty>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/11/bethnal-green-2004.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052132/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/11/bethnal-green-2004.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''1970s\u20131990s IRA bombing campaign'''\n:During the [[Provisional IRA campaign 1969\u20131997|1970s\u20131990s IRA bombing campaign]] throughout the last quarter of the 20th century, several major bombings were carried out in London by the [[Provisional IRA]], including at the [[Palace of Westminster]], [[Tower of London]], and [[Harrods]]. A list of these and other bombings in London to which the LFB responded can be found [[London bombings|here]].\n* '''Dudgeons Wharf, 1969'''\n:[[J & W Dudgeon|Dudgeons Wharf]] on the [[Isle of Dogs]] contained a site of over 100 tanks of various capacities up to 20,000 gallons<ref>{{cite news | title = 5 firemen killed in explosion |newspaper = The Times | date = 18 July 1969 | page = 1|issue=57615 }}</ref> used for storing oils and spirits. A fire started when workmen were cutting up old oil tanks. The LFB was called \u2013 six pumps, a foam tender and the fireboat ''[[Massey Shaw]]'' \u2013 and while firefighters tackled the fire an oil tank exploded. Five firefighters from Millwall and Poplar stations were killed, the largest single loss of life in the LFB since the Second World War.<ref name=LineOfDuty /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firehouse.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-92474.html|title=The Dudgeons Wharf Explosion.... 17th July 1969|work=Firehouse|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928115304/http://www.firehouse.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-92474.html|archivedate=28 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568275/The-toll-of-duty.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Gray | title=The toll of duty | date=4 November 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113140958/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568275/The-toll-of-duty.html | archivedate=13 January 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Bishopsgate goods yard, 1964''' (40 pumps, 12 turntable ladders)\n:London's main railway goods terminal at {{rws|Bishopsgate}} was gutted by a spectacular fire in December 1964. Within 37 minutes of the first crews arriving on scene, the scale of the blaze was so intense and widespread that 40 fire engines had been mobilised. In addition, 12 turntable ladders, two hose layers, two emergency tenders, and 235 firefighters battled the fire which killed two customs officials and destroyed hundreds of railway wagons, dozens of motor vehicles and millions of pounds worth of goods. The site remained derelict for the next 30 years until being rebuilt as [[Shoreditch High Street railway station]].<ref name=journal /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fireservice.co.uk/history-articles/bishopsgate|title=Bishopsgate Goods Depot|work=fireservice.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127132143/http://www.fireservice.co.uk/history-articles/bishopsgate|archivedate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Smithfield market, 1958''' (50 pumps)\n:Over the course of firefighting operations at London's central meat market in January 1958, a total of 389 fire engines with more than 1,700 firefighters from 58 fire stations worked in shifts to tackle a fire of exceptional proportions.<ref name=journal />\n:After the initial call, the LFB mobilised three pumps, a turntable ladder and emergency tender at 2:18 a.m. Upon arrival, a station officer and firefighter from Clerkenwell station headed down into the basement where it was apparent a major fire had broken out. Both became trapped in the basement cellars and suffocated to death. Excessive heat, dense smoke and worsening conditions meant crews had to be rotated as frequently as every 15 minutes, as firefighters suffered from severe heat exhaustion.\n:Twenty-four hours later, with 800 oxygen cylinders used, the fire in the basement suddenly broke up into the first floor of the market, with flames seeping 100&nbsp;ft in the air, engulfing the entire market. The fire, although brought under control and reduced, was not fully extinguished for two weeks. Valuable lessons were learnt after the Smithfield blaze, including introducing a tally system of firefighters' locations and quantity of breathing apparatus.\n:On the 50th anniversary of the Smithfield blaze, in 2008, the then Deputy Commissioner of the LFB said: \"This was a landmark fire in the history of London and its fire brigade. It is important that we remember this tragic fire and honour the memory of the two London firefighters who lost their lives.\"<ref name=\"londonfirejournal.blogspot.com\">{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/smithfield-market-1958.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708051647/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/smithfield-market-1958.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Covent Garden warehouse fire, 1954'''\n:While fighting a fire in a five-storey warehouse adjacent to [[Covent Garden]], a station officer and firefighter, both of Clerkenwell station, were killed. Six more were hospitalised, with three requiring plastic surgery treatment.<ref name=\"londonfirejournal.blogspot.com\" />\n* '''London Blitz'''\n:On 7 September 1940, a sub-officer at West Ham fire station witnessed the start of [[the Blitz]] by Nazi Germany on London. He reported that three miles of waterfront buildings had become a continuous blaze, and ordered 500 fire engines to be mobilised. The commander thought this an exaggeration and sent someone to investigate the situation, who reported back that 1,000 were required. More than 300 firefighters perished in the widespread and sustained bombing campaign, including two in a direct hit on Soho fire station and six in a direct hit on Wandsworth fire station.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Crystal Palace fire, 1936''' (88 pumps)\n:A major fire which led to the complete [[The Crystal Palace#Destruction by fire|destruction of the Crystal Palace]] on 30 November 1936 was attended by 88 fire engines and 438 firefighters from the London Fire Brigade and three other brigades, plus 749 police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2007/05/21/fire_destroyed_feature.shtml|title=Crystal Palace|work=BBC News|date=24 October 2014|access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Colonial Wharf, 1935''' (60 pumps)\n:An eight-storey rubber warehouse in Wapping High Street burned for four days from 27 September 1935, with 60 fire engines in attendance. It was the first major incident for one of the LFB's most famous fireboats, the ''[[Massey Shaw]]'', which greatly assisted land crews, who were hampered by inaccessibility, by supplying a vast water jet to allow the land crews to regroup and prevent the fire from spreading to adjoining warehouses.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Vauxhall, 1918'''\n:A fire on 30 January 1918 claimed the lives of seven London firefighters.<ref name=journal /> Staff at Vauxhall fire station were alerted to the incident by a passer-by, and upon arrival found a three-storey private house well alight, with the roof and upper floor partially collapsed. The fire was extinguished within two hours but firefighters remained in the building dampening down. It was then, while the men were on the ground floor, that the building suffered a total structural collapse. Six firefighters died on scene, one later from severe injury, and two suffered lesser injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005_11_01_archive.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052248/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005_11_01_archive.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable exercises ===\n{{Expand list|date=July 2016}}\n* '''[[Exercise Unified Response]], 2016'''\n:London Fire Brigade led the planning and staging of a large, multi-agency exercise at multiple sites in London, simulating the collapse of Waterloo station onto an underground train.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/exercise-unified-response.asp |title=Exercise Unified Response |accessdate=18 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727031111/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/exercise-unified-response.asp |archivedate=27 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n*'''''London's Firefighters''''': Edited by David C Pike and published by [[Austin Macauley Publishers]] ({{ISBN|978-1-78455-541-2}}) in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinmacauley.com/|title=Austin Macauley Publishers -- Books, eBooks & audiobooks|website=www.austinmacauley.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321133515/http://austinmacauley.com/|archivedate=21 March 2018}}</ref> A wonderfully readable, lavishly illustrated anthology of articles, fiction and verse about the London Fire Brigade, much of it drawn from the award-winning in-house magazine 'London Fireman' (1966\u201382) and 'London Firefighter' (1982\u20132005). The book celebrates the forthcoming 150th anniversary of London's fire brigade's (1866\u20132016) by delivering both a comprehensive history of the London Fire Brigade and provides a fascinating portrait of individual firemen and firewomen at work and (occasionally) at play. The numerous, often highly dramatic illustrations, many from the London Fire Brigade and the Mary Evans Picture Library <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maryevans.com/|title=Mary Evans Picture Library. Historical images. Historical archive. Images of history. Images. Pictures. History. ILN. Stock. Photos Fine Art. Illustrations.|first=Mary Evans Picture Library, London|last=(http://www.maryevans.com)|website=www.maryevans.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208022252/http://www.maryevans.com/|archivedate=8 December 2017}}</ref> offer a lively commentary on the text.\n* '''''Beyond the Flames''''': Written by David C Pike and published by Austin Macauley Publishers ({{ISBN|978-1-84963-396-3}}) in 2013.<ref>[http://www.austinmacauley.com/authors_info.php?manufacturers_id=368 ''David C. Pike''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826090947/http://www.austinmacauley.com/authors_info.php?manufacturers_id=368 |date=26 August 2014 }}, Austin Macauley Publishers Ltd, 2014</ref> It is a personal, insider's account of the life and history of the London Fire Brigade from 1965 to the late 1990s. This book was runner-up in the 2014 [[The People's Book Prize (UK)]] (the UK's prestigious first-time author literary award) and was nominated for the Beryl Bainbridge Award 2014. In 2015 Beyond the Flames was a finalist in the (Wishing Shelf Independent Books Awards). David Pike was awarded the [[Queen's Commendation for Brave Conduct]], and went on to rise to senior rank and organised many of the Brigade's most high-profile events in the early 1990s.\n* '''''Fire Wars:''''' In July 2003, the BBC followed the arson investigators of the LFB's fire investigation unit. The two-part series looked at how the LFB investigated \"4,000 fires where the cause was unknown\". The second programme, ''Fire Wars: Murder Most Foul'', centred on one investigation.<ref>Fire Wars, Produced by Folio/Mentorn for BBC Television transmitted on 1 July 2003 & 8 July 2003</ref>\n* '''''London's Burning:''''' The [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] television series ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'' was based on the fictional Blackwall fire station and centred on characters of the station's blue watch. It was originally a 1986 television film, written by [[Jack Rosenthal]]. The fire station used as the principal location in the drama was Dockhead, near [[London Bridge]], before moving to Leyton fire station in east London late in the series.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095537/ London's Burning: The Movie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050305180838/http://imdb.com/title/tt0095537/ |date=5 March 2005 }}, (IMDB)</ref> The series that followed the film ran from 1988 to 2002.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0123355/ \"London's Burning\" TV series] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913194515/http://imdb.com/title/tt0123355/ |date=13 September 2007 }}, (IMDB)</ref>\n* '''''Fire!:''''' The LFB's Kingsland Road fire station in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], east London, was the focus of a documentary series by [[Thames Television]] for ITV, broadcast in the spring of 1991.<ref>Fire! Produced & directed by Chris Oxley/Laurel Productions for Thames Television/ITV transmitted in 1991</ref> The documentary brought about an internal inquiry by the LFB after scenes were shown of firefighters having a food fight at a Christmas party in one of the programmes. Several watch members from Kingsland Road were suspended after the programme was broadcast on 27 June 1991.<ref>Ban on Party Firemen, Another TV Row, Pub Daily Mail, 28 June 1991</ref>\n* '''''Fireman! A Personal Account:''''' Former London firefighter [[Neil Wallington]] wrote an account of his experience in the LFB called ''Fireman! A Personal Account'', published in 1979.<ref name=\"wallington\" /> He chronicled his transition from a firefighter in the Croydon Fire Brigade through to his reaching the rank of station officer in the LFB.  He went on to become the Chief Fire Officer of the Devon fire brigade (now known as [[Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service]]) and has written several books about fire services over the world. Wallington's work outlined the change in working conditions in the LFB in the 1970s, a time that saw the working hours of firefighters reduced and conditions improved.\n* '''''Red Watch:''''' The former [[ITN]] newsreader [[Gordon Honeycombe]] became friendly with Neil Wallington while he was a station officer at [[Paddington]] fire station. In 1976, Honeycombe published  an account of the [[Worsley Hotel fire]], a major fire at a hostel in [[Maida Vale]] in 1974 that claimed the lives of seven people including one firefighter. The resulting book was called ''Red Watch'';<ref>Red Watch: The best seller about a fire and the men who fought it, by Gordon Honeycombe, Pub Arrow, 17 May 1976, {{ISBN|0-09-126310-7}}</ref> it provided a graphic account of a single incident, and outlined some of the changes to working practices that resulted from it.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Cyril Demarne]]\n* [[Fire Service College]]\n* [[FireLink]]\n* [[List of fire departments]]\n* [[List of British firefighters killed in the line of duty]]\n* [[London Air Ambulance]]\n* [[London Fire Brigade equipment]]\n* [[London Salvage Corps]]\n* [[Metropolitan Police Service]]\n* [[National Fire Savers Credit Union]]\n* [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/ London Fire Brigade]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090808003905/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Stationsandlocations.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Find your local fire station]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130412082906/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WomenInTheBrigade.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Women in the Brigad]\n* [http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/ Dept for Communities and Local Govt: Fire]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060901012330/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts.htm Cabinet Office: Acts of the UK Parliament]\n* [http://www.fbu.org.uk/index.php Fire Brigades Union]\n{{UK fire service}}\n<!---Headquarters building--->\n\n{{Coord|51.50335|-0.09862|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1865 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Fire and rescue services of England]]\n[[Category:Local government in London]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in London]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1865]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|LFB}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox fire department\n| name               = London Fire Brigade\n| logo               = London Fire Brigade Logo.png\n| motto              =\n<!-- Operational Area -->\n| country            = United Kingdom \n| subdivision_type1  = City\n| subdivision_type2  =\n| subdivision_type3  =\n| subdivision_name1  = [[London]]\n| subdivision_name2  =\n| subdivision_name3  =\n| address            = Union Street, {{postcode|SE|1}}\n| coordinates        =\n<!-- Agency Overview -->\n| established        = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1865}}\n| annual calls       = <!-- Include {{small|(1234)}} to indicate year of data -->\n| employees          = 5,992\n| annual budget      = \u00a3389.2 million<ref>http://moderngov.london-fire.gov.uk/mgconvert2pdf.aspx?id=2909</ref>\n| staffing           =\n| chief              = \n| captain            =\n| ALSorBLS           = <!-- [[advanced life support|ALS]] and/or [[basic life support|BLS]] -->\n<!-- Facilities & Equipment -->\n| reference1         = <ref name=\"LFB\" />\n| commissioner       =[[Andy Roe]] <ref name=\"Cotton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/first-woman-takes-over-at-london-fire-brigade-as-chief-retires-after-almost-a-decade-a3425826.html|title=First woman takes over at London Fire Brigade as chief retires after almost a decade|publisher=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=30 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230232639/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/first-woman-takes-over-at-london-fire-brigade-as-chief-retires-after-almost-a-decade-a3425826.html|archivedate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n| divisions          = 5\n| stations           = 103\n|  DPLs           = 47\n|  Pumps           = 55\n|  Pump-Ladders   = 55\n| FRU             = 15\n| TLs    = 4\n|  HPs           = 4\n|  ALPs          = 11 \n| USAR               = 14\n| Fire Boats = 2        \n\n<!-- Footer -->\n| reference2         = <ref name=\"LFB\" />\n| website            = {{Official website|http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/}}\n}}\n<!--Do not edit or change the number of fire stations without first referring to/discussing on the article's talk page-->\nThe '''London Fire Brigade''' ('''LFB''') is the [[statute|statutory]] [[Fire department|fire and rescue service]] for [[London]]. It was formed by the Metropolitan Fire Brigade Act 1865, under the leadership of superintendent [[Eyre Massey Shaw]].\n\nThe LFB is the busiest of all the [[fire services in the United Kingdom]]. It is the second largest in size, after the national [[Scottish Fire and Rescue Service]], and has the largest number of full-time firefighters. It has 5,992&nbsp;staff, including 5,096 operational [[firefighter]]s and officers based at 102 [[fire station]]s (plus one river station).<ref name=\"LFB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WhoWeAre.asp|title=Who we are|publisher=London Fire Brigade|accessdate=9 April 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429034538/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WhoWeAre.asp|archivedate=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Who we are|url=http://www.firescotland.gov.uk/about-us/whoweare.aspx|publisher=Scottish Fire and Rescue Service|accessdate=22 June 2014|quote=any of our 8,000 firefighters|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103211706/http://www.firescotland.gov.uk/about-us/whoweare.aspx|archivedate=3 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe LFB is led by the Commissioner for Fire and Emergency Planning, Andy Roe. The brigade and Commissioner are overseen by the [[Greater London Authority]], which in April 2018 took over these responsibilities from the [[London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority]] (LFEPA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about-us/governance-london-fire-commissioner/|title=Governance - London Fire Commissioner|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2015-16 financial year the LFB received 171,488 emergency calls. These consisted of: 20,773 fires, 48,696 false alarms of fire and 30,066 other calls for service.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2015-16.pdf|title=LFEPA|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611020709/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2015-16.pdf|archivedate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"data.london.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/london-fire-brigade---whole-of-service-incident-summary-report-by-financial-year |title=Archived copy |accessdate=5 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206105337/https://data.london.gov.uk/dataset/london-fire-brigade---whole-of-service-incident-summary-report-by-financial-year |archivedate=6 February 2017  }}</ref> As well as [[firefighting]], the LFB also responds to road [[traffic collision]]s, [[flood]]s, trapped-in-[[elevator|lift]] releases, and other incidents such as those involving [[Dangerous goods|hazardous materials]] or major transport accidents. It also conducts [[Emergency preparedness|emergency planning]] and performs [[fire safety]] inspections and education. It does not provide an [[ambulance]] service as this function is performed by the [[London Ambulance Service]] as an independent [[NHS trust]], although all LFB firefighters are trained in first aid and all of [[London Fire Brigade appliances|its fire engine]]s carry first aid equipment. Since 2016, the LFB has provided first aid for some life-threatening medical emergencies (e.g. cardiac or respiratory arrest).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_brigade-and-london-ambulance-service-team-up-for-life-saving-trial.asp#.WIpXBH2DEfI|title=News|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813185751/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_brigade-and-london-ambulance-service-team-up-for-life-saving-trial.asp#.WIpXBH2DEfI|archivedate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:DV307 no.50 The great fire, London June 23 1861 at 2.30am from Billingsgate.png|thumb|The 1861 Tooley Street fire from Billingsgate]]\nFollowing a multitude of ad-hoc firefighting arrangements and the [[Great Fire of London]], various insurance companies established firefighting units to tackle fires that occurred in buildings that their respective companies insured. As demands grew on the primitive firefighting units they began to coordinate and co-operate with each other until, on 1 January 1833, the London Fire Engine Establishment was formed under the leadership of [[James Braidwood (firefighter)|James Braidwood]], who had founded the first professional, municipal fire brigade in [[Edinburgh]].<ref name=LFBHist>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade: Key dates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> He introduced a uniform that, for the first time, included personal protection from the hazards of firefighting. With 80 [[firefighter]]s and 13 [[fire station]]s, the unit was still a private enterprise, funded by the insurance companies and as such was responsible mainly for saving material goods from fire.\n\nSeveral large fires, most notably at the [[Palace of Westminster]] in 1834<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade | History, key dates (Our history)<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> and the [[1861 Tooley Street fire]] (in which Braidwood died in action, aged 61),<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /><ref>[[Tooley Street#Tooley Street fire, 1861|Tooley Street Fire]]</ref> spurred the insurance companies to lobby the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] to provide the brigade at public expense and management. After due consideration, in 1865 the Metropolitan Fire Brigade Act was passed,<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> creating the Metropolitan Fire Brigade under the leadership of [[Eyre Massey Shaw]], a former head of police and fire services in [[Belfast]]. In 1904 it was renamed as the London Fire Brigade.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> The LFB moved into a new headquarters built by [[Higgs and Hill]]<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49753 General introduction', Survey of London: volume 26: Lambeth: Southern area (1956), pp. 1\u201317.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605014439/http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=49753 |date=5 June 2011 }} Date accessed: 27 March 2010.</ref> on the [[Albert Embankment]] in Lambeth in 1937, where it remained until 2007.<ref name=geo>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/832436|title=Lambeth: London Fire Brigade... (C) Nigel Cox :: Geograph Britain and Ireland|author=Nigel Cox|work=geograph.org.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012150842/http://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/832436|archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:South London warehouse fire 1980.jpg|thumb|right|LFB firefighters at a warehouse in south London after a major fire in 1980]]\nDuring the [[World War II|Second World War]] the country's brigades were amalgamated into a single [[National Fire Service]]. The separate London Fire Brigade for the [[County of London]] was re-established in 1948.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> With the formation of [[Greater London]] in 1965, this absorbed most of the Middlesex Fire Brigade, the borough brigades for [[County Borough of West Ham|West Ham]], [[County Borough of East Ham|East Ham]] and [[County Borough of Croydon|Croydon]] and parts of the [[Essex County Fire and Rescue Service|Essex]], [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service|Hertfordshire]], [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service|Surrey]] and [[Kent Fire and Rescue Service|Kent]] brigades.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" />\n\nIn 1986 the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) was disbanded and a new statutory authority, the [[London Fire and Civil Defence Authority]] (LFCDA), was formed to take responsibility for the LFB.<ref name=\"LFBHist\" /> The LFCDA was replaced in 2000 by the London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/FireAuthority.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101004173458/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/FireAuthority.asp|archivedate=4 October 2010}}</ref> At the same time, the [[Greater London Authority]] (GLA) was established to administer the LFEPA and coordinate emergency planning for London. Consisting of the [[Mayor of London]] and other elected members, the GLA also takes responsibility for the [[Metropolitan Police Service]], [[Transport for London]] and other functions.\n\nIn 2007 the LFB vacated its Lambeth headquarters and moved to a site in Union Street, [[Southwark]]. In the same year, the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] announced that LFB Commissioner [[Ken Knight]] had been appointed as the first [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Fire Services|Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser]] to the government.<ref>Communities and Local Government News Release 099, 24 May 2007, New Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser Appointed</ref> Knight was succeeded as Commissioner at that time by [[Ron Dobson]], who served for almost ten years. Dany Cotton took over in 2017, becoming the brigade's first female commissioner.<ref name=\"Cotton\" />\n\n=== Commissioners and chief officers ===\nAs of 1 January 2020 Andy Roe is the commissioner of the LFB. He succeeds [[Dany Cotton]], who in 2017 had become the first woman to hold the top role; Cotton resigned in the wake of the [[Grenfell Tower fire]] after 32 years' service in the brigade. Prior to Cotton, [[Ron Dobson]] was the commissioner and he had served in the LFB since 1979; he was awarded a [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] for his distinguished contribution to the fire service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_PR1543.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=12 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061616/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_PR1543.asp |archivedate=11 August 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* 1833 to 1861: [[James Braidwood (firefighter)|James Braidwood]] (director of the London Fire Engine Establishment, [[1861 Tooley Street fire|died in action]])<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade: key dates, (accessed 23 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref>\n* 1861 to 1891: [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Capt.]] [[Eyre Massey Shaw]] (superintendent, later chief officer)\n* 1891 to 1896: James Sexton Simmonds\n* 1896 to 1903: [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Capt.]] Lionel de Latour Wells\n* 1903 to 1909: [[Rear admiral (Royal Navy)|RAdm.]] James de Courcy Hamilton\n* 1909 to 1918: [[Lieutenant commander|Lt. Cdr.]] Sir Sampson Sladen\n* 1918 to 1933: Arthur Reginald Dyer, KPM<ref>Royal Warrant</ref>\n* 1933 to 1938: [[Major (United Kingdom)|Maj.]] Cyril Morris, MC<ref>http://www.thegazette.co.uk/all-notices/content/100068</ref>\n* 1938 to 1941: [[Commander (Royal Navy)|Cdr.]] Sir [[Aylmer Firebrace]], CBE\n* 1939 to 1941: Maj. Frank Jackson, CBE\n* ''1941 to 1948: [[National Fire Service|all fire brigades nationalised]]''\n* 1948 to 1962: Sir [[Frederick Delve]], CBE\n* 1962 to 1970: [[Leslie Leete]], CBE\n* 1970 to 1976: [[Joseph Milner (firefighter)|Joseph Milner]]\n* 1976 to 1980: Peter Darby\n* 1980 to 1987: Ronald Bullers\n* 1987 to 1991: Gerald Clarkson\n* 1991 to 2003: Brian Robinson, CBE (first commissioner)\n* 2003 to 2007: Sir [[Ken Knight]], CBE\n* 2007 to 2016: [[Ron Dobson]], CBE\n* 2017 to 2019: [[Dany Cotton]]\n* 2020 to present: Andy Roe\n\n== Organisation ==\n[[File:LFB Headquarters.JPG|thumb|London Fire Brigade headquarters from 1937 to 2007, in [[Lambeth]].]]\n[[File:London Fire Brigade HQ.jpg|thumb|The LFB's current headquarters since 2007, in [[Southwark]].]]\nHistorically, the London Fire Brigade was organised into two divisions: Northern and Southern, divided in most places by the [[River Thames]] and each commanded by a Divisional Officer. Both divisions were divided into three districts, each under a Superintendent with his headquarters at a \"superintendent station\". The superintendent stations themselves were commanded by District Officers, with the other stations under Station Officers.<ref name=\"info\">London Fire Brigade, ''The London Fire Brigade: Information for Intending Candidates'', December 1938.</ref>\n\nOn the creation of the [[Greater London Council]] in 1965, the brigade was enlarged and took over almost all of the Middlesex Fire Brigade, part of west Kent, North Surrey and South West Essex, together with the small County Borough brigades of Croydon, East Ham and West Ham.\n\nThe internal LFB organisation consists of three directorates that all report to the Commissioner. They are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/SeniorManagementTeam.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822095316/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/SeniorManagementTeam.asp|archivedate=22 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n* Operations;\n* Safety and Assurance;\n* Finance and Contractual Services.\n\nThe LFB's headquarters since 2007 is located in Union Street in [[Southwark]], adjacent to the brigade's training centre, which is both the original headquarters of the Massey Shaw fire brigade and his home, Winchester House, as well as the [[London Fire Brigade Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LFBHeadquarters.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925040029/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LFBHeadquarters.asp|archivedate=25 September 2010|access-date=4 October 2010}}</ref> The brigade was previously headquartered in [[Lambeth]] between 1937 and 2007.\n\n== Legislative powers ==\nFire and rescue authorities in England come under the government department formerly known as the Office of the Deputy Prime Minister (ODPM).  This department was responsible for legislation covering fire authorities; however, in 2006, a structural change to central government led to the  creation of the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] (DCLG).  It is now responsible for fire and resilience in England, including London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/|title=Fire prevention and rescue|work=communities.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318152355/http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/|archivedate=18 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004]] changed many working practices;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents|title=Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004|work=legislation.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916025154/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents|archivedate=16 September 2015}}</ref> it was brought in to replace the [[Fire Services Act 1947]] and repealed several existing acts, many going back fifty years. The full list of acts repealed can be found here:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents#sch2|title=Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004|work=legislation.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916025154/http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2004/21/contents#sch2|archivedate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2004 Act was drafted in response to the Independent Review of the Fire Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irfs.org.uk/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928110005/http://www.irfs.org.uk/|title=irfs.org.uk|archivedate=28 September 2007|work=irfs.org.uk}}</ref> often referred to as the Bain Report, after its author [[George Bain (academic)|Professor Sir George Bain]].  It recommended radical changes to many working procedures and led to a [[UK firefighter dispute 2002\u20132003|national firefighter strike in 2002\u20132003]].\n\nFurther changes to the legislative, organisational and structural fabric of the brigade, which could include varying the attendance time, the location of frontline appliances and number of personnel, plus mandatory performance targets, priorities and objectives are set by the DCLG in the form of a document called the Fire and Rescue Service National Framework. The framework is set annually by the government and applies to all brigades in England. Responsibility for the rest of the UK fire service is devolved to the various parliaments and assemblies. On country-wide issues, the [[Chief Fire Officers Association]] provides the collective voice on fire, rescue and resilience issues.<ref>[http://www.cfoa.org.uk/cfoa_public/ Chief Fire Officers Association] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060821225957/http://www.cfoa.org.uk/cfoa_public/ |date=21 August 2006 }}</ref> Membership is made up from senior officers above the rank of Assistant Chief Officer, to Chief Fire Officer (or the new title of Brigade Manager).\n\n== Staffing ==\n\n=== Rank structure ===\n[[File:Pride in London 2016 - London Fire Brigade with fire engine participating in the parade.png|alt=Two firefighters in red \"LFB PRIDE\" tshirts walk in a parade alongside a fire engine. The fire engine is decorated with at least five rainbow flags.|thumb|Staff of the London Fire Brigade as part of the Pride in London 2016 parade.]]\nThe London Fire Brigade, along with many UK fire and rescue services adopted a change in rank structure in 2006. The traditional ranks were replaced in the LFB, by new titles more descriptive to the job function.<ref>[http://www.ipds.co.uk/cd/fund.asp The Integrated Personal Development System (IPDS) (accessed 8 October 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007051312/http://www.ipds.co.uk/cd/fund.asp |date=7 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/rank_structure.asp London Fire Brigade: Rank structure] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904115633/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/rank_structure.asp |date=4 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2019, London Fire Brigade announced they are be returning to some of the old titles.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Current title || Rank markings\n|-\n|Firefighter ||  [[File:Capture FF insignia.jpg|80px]]\n|-\n|[[Leading Firefighter]] ||  [[File:Leading Firefighter.jpg|80px|]]\n|-\n|[[Sub-Officer]]|| [[File:Capture CM.JPG|80px]] \n|-\n|[[Station officer|Station Officer]]|| [[File:Capture WM.JPG|80px]] \n|-\n|Station Commander ||[[File:Capture SM.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Group Commander (also Borough Commander) ||[[File:Capture AM.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Deputy Assistant Commissioner||[[File:Capture daco.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n|Assistant Commissioner||[[File:Capture aco.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n| Deputy Commissioner ||[[File:Capture DCO.JPG|80px]]\n|-\n|Commissioner for Fire and Emergency Planning ||[[File:Capture co.JPG|80px]]\n|}\n\n=== Historical ranks ===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!1833\u20131938||1938\u20131965||1965\u20131992||1992\u20132001||2001\u20132003 || 2003-2019\n|-\n|Fireman 4th Class||Fireman||Fireman/Firewoman||colspan=3|Firefighter\n|-\n|Fireman 3rd Class||Senior Fireman||Leading Fireman/Firewoman||Leading Firefighter||Crew Commander (A)||N/A\n|-\n|Fireman 2nd Class||Sub-Officer||Sub-Officer||Sub-Officer||Crew Commander (B)<br />(or Watch Commander A [one-pump stations only])||Crew Manager\n|-\n|Fireman 1st Class||Station Officer||Station Officer||Station Officer||Watch Commander (B)||Watch Manager A/B\n|-\n|Junior Fireman||Assistant District Officer||Assistant Divisional Officer <br />(Station Commander from 1986)|| Assistant Divisional Officer<br />(or Station Commander)||colspan=2|Station Commander (or Deputy Group Commander)\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Senior Fireman||District Officer||Divisional Officer||Divisional Officer||colspan=2|Divisional Officer<br />(or Group Commander)\n|-\n|Senior District Officer||Deputy Assistant Chief Officer||colspan=3|Assistant Chief Officer (or Area Commander)\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Deputy Superintendent||rowspan=2|Deputy Chief Officer||Deputy Chief Fire Officer||rowspan=2 colspan=4|Deputy Chief Officer\n|-\n|Assistant Chief Fire Officer<br />(or Area Commander)\n|-\n|Superintendent||colspan=5|Chief Officer\n|}\n\n=== Recruitment and training ===\nIn the last 24 months the LFB have run 3 firefighter recruitment campaigns, however in previous years have seen fewer or even none. There are many factors as to why they would run a recruitment drive, as there is actually no set recruitment drive for firefighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/lfb_firefighter_recruitment#incoming-916441|title=LFB Firefighter Recruitment - a Freedom of Information request to London Fire Commissioner (London Fire Brigade)|date=4 December 2016|website=whatdotheyknow.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118043613/https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/lfb_firefighter_recruitment#incoming-916441|archivedate=18 January 2017}}</ref>\nProfessional firefighter training usually takes place at various London venues. On successful completion, the newly qualified firefighter is posted to a fire station to work on a shift pattern&nbsp;\u2013 currently two day shifts (ten and half hours), followed by two night shifts (thirteen and half hours), followed by four days off. Working patterns were the subject of scrutiny in Professor Bain's Independent Review of the Fire Service.<ref>[http://www.irfs.org.uk/atoz.htm Independent Review of the Fire Service, Prof Sir George Bain Pub: 16 Dec 2002] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001152517/http://www.irfs.org.uk/atoz.htm |date=1 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\nAfter training school, firefighters serve a one-year period of probation; qualification and full pay are not reached until the candidate completes a development folder which usually takes around 12\u201318 months. Ongoing training&nbsp;\u2013 both theoretical and practical&nbsp;\u2013 continues throughout the firefighter's career.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/recruitment/ff_training.asp London Fire Brigade: Training] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903085855/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/recruitment/ff_training.asp |date=3 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\n=== Shift pattern ===\nIn December 2010 the LFB and [[Fire Brigades Union]] (FBU) agreed on a new shift pattern for front-line firefighters: two 10\u00bd-hour day shifts then two 13\u00bd-hour night shifts followed by four days off.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12063474 | work=BBC News | title=London firefighters row over shift patterns resolved | date=22 December 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225170238/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12063474 | archivedate=25 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe agreement followed two 8-hour daytime [[Industrial action|strikes]] by the FBU<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1462.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Error Page<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029034734/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1462.asp |date=29 October 2010 }}</ref> in protest at the LFB's intention to change the shift pattern from two 9-hour day shifts then two 15-hour night shifts followed by three days off, to two 12-hour day shifts then two 12-hour night shifts followed by four days off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personneltoday.com/articles/2010/09/23/56604/firefighters-to-begin-industrial-action-in-dispute-over-shift.html|title=Firefighters to begin industrial action in dispute over shift patterns|work=Personnel Today|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924174037/http://www.personneltoday.com/articles/2010/09/23/56604/firefighters-to-begin-industrial-action-in-dispute-over-shift.html|archivedate=24 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nA London Fire Brigade report published in March 2012 stated that the shift changes have improved safety in the city. Compared with the 12 months prior to the shift changes, the 12 months following them saw firefighters able to spend more time on training, community safety work, and home safety visits (including the free fitting of smoke alarms).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_D034CCBEDCBB4498B9838A10FA89B43F.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323145935/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_D034CCBEDCBB4498B9838A10FA89B43F.asp |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Promotion ===\nIn order for a firefighter to gain promotion he or she must go through an assessment centre and reach the required standard set out by the Brigade. This process will be followed for each subsequent role the individual applies for, up to and including Assistant Commissioner. Appointments above the role of Assistant Commissioner are overseen by elected members of The London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/OurStaff.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323105551/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/OurStaff.asp|archivedate=23 March 2015|access-date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome promotion exams can be substituted by qualifications from the [[Institution of Fire Engineers]]. Firefighters and civilians such as building inspectors, scientists, surveyors and other practising professionals, take these qualifications either by written test or research.\n\nFuture promotion exams will be set using the Integrated Personal Development System (IPDS).<ref>[http://www.ipds.co.uk/public/site/newsdocs112/IPDS%20Booklet.pdf Integrated Personal Development System Booklet], (PDF download) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001185317/http://www.ipds.co.uk/public/site/newsdocs112/IPDS%20Booklet.pdf |date=1 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\n== Firefighting, special services and fire prevention ==\nIn 2010/11, the LFB handled a total of 212,657 emergency calls, including 5,241 [[prank call|hoax calls]] (although it only mobilised to 2,248 of those malicious false alarms). During the same period, it dealt with 13,367 major fires. There were 6,731 dwelling fires, including 748 that had been started deliberately; 73 people died in 58 fatal fires.\n\nIn addition to [[conflagration]]s, LFB firefighters respond to \"special services\".<ref name=\"frsa\">[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#7 Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004, published online the Office of Public Sector Information, (accessed 6 Nov 07)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190108/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#7 |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n[[File:LFB in action.jpg|thumb|right|LFB firefighters at a building fire; one uses an axe (right) to gain entry]]\n\nA special service is defined as every other non-fire related emergency, such as:<ref name=\"2010/11rpt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/Our_performance_2010-11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 June 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105112459/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/Our_performance_2010-11.pdf |archivedate=5 January 2012  }}</ref>\n* [[Elevator|Lift]] releases (9,395 in 2010/11);\n* Effecting entry/exit (7,276 in 2010/11);\n* [[Flood]]ing (6,956 in 2010/11);\n* [[Traffic collision]]s (3,604 in 2010/11);\n* Spills and leaks (1,479 in 2010/11);\n* Assisting other agencies (855 in 2010/11);\n* \"Making safe\" operations (782 in 2010/11);\n* Animal rescues (583 in 2010/11);\n* Hazardous materials incidents (353 in 2010/11);\n* General evacuations (322 in 2010/11);\n* Suicides or attempts (229 in 2010/11); and\n* Waterborne rescues (38 in 2010/11).\n\nThe full scope of the brigade's duties and powers is enshrined in the Fire and Rescue Act 2004.\n\nFirefighters and, in some cases, specialist teams from the brigade's [[fire investigation]] unit, based at Dowgate, also investigate [[arson]] incidents, often working alongside the police and providing evidence in court. In 2008/09, deliberate fires accounted for 28% of all those attended by the LFB, a 28% reduction on the previous year.<ref name=\"london-fire.gov.uk\">{{cite web | url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2013-14.pdf | title=Our Performance 2013/2014 | accessdate=9 April 2015 | format=pdf | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005032701/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Documents/our-performance-2013-14.pdf | archivedate=5 October 2015 | url-status=live | website=london-fire.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe other core duty of the brigade is to \"prevent damage\", and day-to-day fire prevention duties.\n\n=== Firefighting cover ===\n[[File:Sydenham substation fire.jpg|thumb|right|The LFB tackles a fire at an [[electrical substation]] in [[Sydenham, London|Sydenham]].<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LastestIncidentsContainer_0B1355AE515C497D8CCEF7A1CE421B1A.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Upper Sydenham \u2013 electrical sub-station fire<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128060530/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LastestIncidentsContainer_0B1355AE515C497D8CCEF7A1CE421B1A.asp |date=28 November 2011 }}</ref>]]\nThe LFB provides fire cover according to a system of four risk categories which have traditionally been used across the UK, where every building is rated for its risk on a scale from \"A\" down to \"D\". The risk category determines the minimum number of appliances to be sent in a pre-determined mobilisation.\n\nCategory \"A\" includes areas with a high density of large buildings and/or population, such as offices or factories. Three fire engines are to arrive at \"A\" risks within eight minutes, the first two within five minutes.\n\nAreas with a medium density of large buildings and/or population, such as multi-storey residential blocks, will generally be classified \"B\" risk. Two fire engines will be deployed, with one to arrive within five minutes and the second within eight minutes.\n\nCategory \"C\" covers lower density, suburban areas and detached properties. One fire engine should arrive at a \"C\" risk incident within ten minutes. More rural areas not covered by the first three categories will be considered \"D\" risk. One fire engine should arrive at \"D\" risks within 20 minutes.\n\n=== Response times ===\n[[File:LFB dampening down after blaze.jpg|thumb|right|Damping down using an aerial ladder platform after a fire in Camden]]\nIn 2007/08, the first fire engine mobilised to a 999 call arrived within five minutes 58.8% of the time, and within eight minutes 90% of the time. The second fire engine deployed arrived within eight minutes 81.9% of the time, and within ten minutes 92.4% of the time.\n\nIn 2010/11, the average response time of the first appliance to the scene was 5 minutes 34 seconds (6 minute target), and the second appliance was 6 minutes 53 seconds (8 minute target).<ref name=\"2010/11rpt\" />\n\nIn 2015/16, the average response time for the first appliance to the scene was 5 minutes 33 seconds (6 minute target), and the second appliance to the scene was 6 minutes 55 seconds (8 minute target).<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==== Mutual assistance ====\nThe Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004 gives the UK fire services the ability to call upon other services or fire authorities in what is known as mutual assistance.<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#13 Fire and Rescue Act 2004] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190108/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts/acts2004/40021--c.htm#13 |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref> For example, the LFB played a comprehensive role in assisting [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]] at the [[Buncefield fire]] in 2005. Much earlier, the Hampton Court fire of 1986, which was on the border with Surrey, was attended by both the LFB and [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]].\n\nIn 2015/16 the LFB assisted at 567 \"over the border\" incidents.<ref name=\"data.london.gov.uk\"/>\n\nThe other fire services that adjoin the LFB are:\n* [[Essex County Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Kent Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Royal Berkshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Buckinghamshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]]\n\nThe LFB also mobilises to support airport firefighters at [[London Heathrow Airport]], [[London City Airport]] and  The London Heliport.\n\n=== Determining the size of an incident ===\n[[File:Fire London 2011Dec.jpg|thumb|right|London Fire Brigade attending an incident in [[St Giles, London|St. Giles]] in December 2011.]]\n\nThe LFB, along with all other UK fire and rescue services, determines the size of a fire or special service by the final number of appliances mobilised to deal with it. For example, two appliances are despatched to a \"B\" risk area in response to a fire call in a residential house.  The officer-in-charge can request additional appliances by transmitting a radio message such as, \"make pumps 4\", or if persons are believed to be involved or trapped, \"make pumps 4, persons reported\".<ref>[http://www.shropshirefire.gov.uk/Docs/BrigadeOrders/Operations/Operations%20No%203%20Part%202%20-%20Incident%20Command%20Radio%20Messages%20-%20Main%20Radio%20Scheme.pdf Shropshire Fire and Rescue Service, Operational Note 3 (in the public domain, accessed 22 May 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630153210/http://www.shropshirefire.gov.uk/Docs/BrigadeOrders/Operations/Operations%20No%203%20Part%202%20-%20Incident%20Command%20Radio%20Messages%20-%20Main%20Radio%20Scheme.pdf |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref> The control room will then deploy a further two appliances making a total of four. Informally, firefighters refer to such fires as 'a make up' or 'a 4-pumper';\n<ref name=\"wallington\">Fireman! A Personal Account, by Neil Wallington, Pub David & Charles, 22 February 1979, {{ISBN|0-7153-7723-X}}</ref> when the fire is out, if no other pumping appliances were despatched, this would be recorded as a '4-pump fire'.\n\nIf an incident is more serious, it can be escalated straight to a 6-, 8- or 10-pump fire and beyond \u2013 in London this is usually completed in even numbers, though it is not uncommon for a 10-pump fire to be 'made up' to 15 if necessary.  A call to, say, a large warehouse ablaze could be escalated straight to a 10-pump fire. The 2007 [[Cutty Sark]] fire required 8 pumps;<ref name=\"press\">[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/latest_incidents.asp London Fire Brigade: Latest information on incidents in London, 21 May 2007 (accessed 22 May 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527000351/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/latest_incidents.asp |date=27 May 2007 }}</ref> as a serious incident escalates, the brigade deploys senior officers, Command Units and any specialist appliances required.\n\nExamples of 25-pump fires include the blaze at [[Alexandra Palace]] in 1980,<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=475 London Fire Brigade press release pr149/02 24 September 2002 (accessed 22 May 07)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021339/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=475 |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> and at the [[The Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust|Royal Marsden Hospital, Chelsea]] in 2008, the latter also involving four aerial appliances. The [[King's Cross fire]] in 1987 was a 30-pump fire,<ref>[http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/DoT_KX1987.pdf Dept of Transport, Investigation into the King's Cross fire: Desmond Fennell OBE, QC, Nov 1988 (accessed 25 October 2007)]</ref> as was the blaze in numerous shops on [[Oxford Street]] in April 2007. The [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in June 2017 was a 40-pump fire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/17/london-fire-brigade-dany-cotton-grenfell-tower|title=London fire brigade boss: \u2018It was a massive risk, but it\u2019s our job to go in\u2019|publisher=The Guardian|date=18 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617204103/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/17/london-fire-brigade-dany-cotton-grenfell-tower|archivedate=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nPumping appliances can only operate with a minimum crew of four, and a maximum of six (although this is rare) so it is possible to estimate the number of firefighters attending an incident by multiplying the number of pumps by five. For example, the Cutty Sark fire was described as \"an 8-pump fire attended by 40 firefighters\".<ref name=\"press\" />\n\n=== Special services ===\nCore services are paid for by London's [[Council Tax|council tax]] payers and through central government funding known as a grant settlement; each council tax payer's bill will include a precept \u2013 a specific part of their bill that contributes to the funding of the fire brigade. Those in need of the LFB's services in an emergency do not pay, but the brigade can provide additional special services for which it may charge where there is no immediate threat to life or imminent risk of injury.\n\nExamples of these special services which may be charged for include the clearing of flooded commercial premises, the use of brigade equipment for supplying or removing water, and making structures safe in cases where there is no risk of personal injury to the public.\n\n=== Safety and fire prevention ===\nLFB firefighters and watch officers often visit residential and commercial premises to advise on hazard risk assessment and fire prevention. They also provide safety education to schools and youth groups.  Each of the London boroughs has a central fire safety office that collates and coordinates fire prevention work in accordance with legislation, and they are supported by a dedicated team of specialist officers.\n\nIn 2010/11, the LFB made 70,016 home fire safety visits. Over 100,000 children are seen each year by the brigade's schools team. Around half of all serious fires occur in the home, and many house fires attended by the LFB no smoke alarm was fitted, despite the LFB fitting tens of thousands in homes every year.\n\n== Stations and equipment ==\n[[File:LFBstn.jpg|thumb|right|[[Dowgate]] fire station in the [[City of London]] is home to the [[fire investigation]] team]]\n[[File:Romford fire station.JPG|thumb|right|[[Romford]] fire station]]\nAs of 2014, the LFB has 103 fire stations, including one river station, across the 32 [[London borough]]s and the [[City of London]].<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_organisation.asp London Fire Brigade: Our Organisation (accessed 16 Jan 07)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208103552/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_organisation.asp |date=8 February 2007 }}</ref> They are staffed 24 hours a day by full-time employees of the brigade, and are linked to a control centre in [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/0DA45C1B1DC14505A4FA14A3D18EFBA0_PR2939.asp#.VZvvdBtVhBc|title=London Fire Brigade|date=1 February 2012|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708032706/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/0DA45C1B1DC14505A4FA14A3D18EFBA0_PR2939.asp#.VZvvdBtVhBc|archivedate=8 July 2015}}</ref> This centre was opened in 2012; calls to it are fed from 999 operators at [[BT Group|BT]], [[Cable & Wireless Worldwide|Cable & Wireless]] and [[Global Crossing]].\n\nCentral London stations can attend up to 8,000 calls per year, inner-city stations about 3,000 to 4,000 calls per year (these tend to be the stations that are busy serving the densely populated areas), and outlying or suburban fire stations may attend around 1,500 calls which include road traffic accidents, grass fires and house fires.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/az/az_stations.asp London Fire Brigade: A-Z of fire stations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212090045/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/az/az_stations.asp |date=12 December 2004 }}</ref>\n\nSome UK fire authorities use retained (part-time) firefighters who live and work near their local station and are on-call, but the LFB is one of only three UK fire services where all operational staff are full-time employees.\n\nEach station has four shifts, or 'watches': red, white, blue and green, with a Watch Manager in charge of each. The overall management of the station falls to the Station Manager, who will also attend serious incidents, as well as spending time on call.\n\nA group of one (City of London) to five (Tower Hamlets) stations within a borough are managed by a Borough Commander (Group Commander) who interacts strategically on a local level with the Borough Commander for the police and ambulance services and the chief executive of the local authority.\n\n=== Stations and districts ===\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/A-ZFireStations.asp Alphabetical fire station listing and addresses from the London Fire Brigade website]\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/150/map-of-london-fire-stations.asp Interactive map of current (status: 2016) and former London Fire Brigade fire stations]\n\nUpon the founding of the London County Council in 1965, the new authority was organised into 11 divisions, of roughly 10 to 12 stations each, designated 'A' Division through to 'L' Division, dispatched by three 999 mobilising control rooms. 'A' (West End), 'D' (West London), 'G' (North West London) and 'J' (North London) mobilised from Wembley (the former Middlesex headquarters); 'B' (Central London south of the river), 'E' (South East London and Kent), 'H' (South London and Surrey) and 'K' (South West London south of the river and Surrey) mobilised from Croydon (the former Croydon County Borough headquarters); finally, 'C' (City and Inner East London), 'F' (East London including Docklands) and 'L' (North East London and South West Essex), mobilised from Stratford (the former West Ham County Borough headquarters). Each of these divisions were, to a degree, autonomous of each other and had their own divisional management hierarchy. This arrangement lasted until 1989 when the brigade was re-organised into the current arrangement.\n\nThe LFB is currently formed into five divisions: Northern, Eastern, Western, Southeastern and Southwestern. As of 2013, 21 fire stations were located in the Northern Division and have [[call sign]]s prefixed \"A\"; 26 were in the Eastern Division with call signs prefixed \"F\"; Western Division consisted of 21 stations with \"G\"-prefixed call signs; 22 were under the Southeastern Division with an \"E\" prefix; and the remaining 22 were based in the Southwestern Division, call signs prefixed \"H\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2008/02/firemans-own-book-containing-accounts.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724160820/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2008/02/firemans-own-book-containing-accounts.html|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> As part of this organisation, many stations were re-coded.\n\nBelow is a complete listing, as of 2014, of the 102 fire stations of the London Fire Brigade according to district and station radio callsign. The LFB is divided into five districts, each designated by a letter of the alphabet: the Northern District Command is designated as \"A\"; the Southeastern District Command is designated as \"E\"; the Eastern District Command is designated as \"F\"; the Western District Command is designated as \"G\"; the Southwestern District Command is designated as \"H\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\n;Northern District\nThe Northern District Command is designated as \"A\" or \"Alpha\". There are currently 17 fire stations in the Northern District. The Northern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[London Borough of Haringey|Haringey]], [[London Borough of Islington|Islington]], the [[City of Westminster]] and the [[City of London]].\n\n;Southeastern District\nThe Southeastern District Command is designated as \"E\" or \"Echo\". There are currently 19 fire stations in the Southeastern District. The Southeastern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[Bexley (London Borough)|Bexley]], [[Bromley (London Borough)|Bromley]], [[Greenwich (London Borough)|Greenwich]], [[Lewisham (London Borough)|Lewisham]], and [[Southwark (London Borough)|Southwark]].\n\n;Eastern District\nThe Eastern District Command is designated as \"F\" or \"Foxtrot\". There are currently 23 fire stations in the Eastern District. The Eastern District serves the following boroughs of London: [[Barking and Dagenham]], [[Hackney (London Borough)|Hackney]]\n, [[Havering (London Borough)|Havering]], [[Newham (London Borough)|Newham]], [[Redbridge (London Borough)|Redbridge]], [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets|Tower Hamlets]], and [[Waltham Forest]].\n\n;Western District\nThe Western District Command is designated as \"G\" or \"Golf\". There are currently 21 fire stations in the Western District. The Western District serves the following boroughs of London: Brent, Ealing, Hammersmith and Fulham, Harrow, Hillingdon, Hounslow, and Kensington and Chelsea.\n\n;Southwestern District\nThe Southwestern District Command is designated as \"H\" or \"Hotel\". There are currently 22 fire stations in the Southwestern District, including the independent River Station, the quarters of the Fireboat. The Southwestern District serves the following boroughs of London: Croydon, Kingston upon Thames, Lambeth, Merton, Richmond upon Thames, Sutton, and Wandsworth.\n\n=== Appliances ===\n{{Main|London Fire Brigade appliances}}\n[[File:1995 London Fire engine.jpg|thumb|right|A 1995-registered pump ladder appliance pictured in 2011 (no longer operational)]]\n[[File:LFB fireboat.JPG|thumb|right|''Fireflash'', registered in 1999, is one of London's two [[fireboat]]s]]\n[[File:One of the LFB's New Appliances.png|thumb|One of the LFB's newest appliances in 2016]]\n[[File:LFB Scania P410 64M Turntable Ladder.jpg|thumb|2020 Scania P410 64M Turntable Ladder]]\n[[File:LFB Scania L360 32M Turntable Ladder.jpg|thumb|2020 Scania L360 32M Turntable Ladder]]\n\nAll 102 LFB stations (not counting the river station) have a conventional [[Fire apparatus|fire appliance]] known as a dual pump ladder. Around 55 stations are also assigned one additional pump. Numerous other stations are home to a range of other specialist vehicles.\n\nThe stations that are assigned both a dual pump ladder and a pump are generally the busier stations receiving over 2,000 emergency calls (known colloquially by firefighters as \"shouts\") per year. They may also be stations of strategic importance, or those located in areas considered to be high risk. The remaining stations equipped with a single pump ladder generally attend fewer than 2,000 calls per year.\n\nAn earlier fleet of mostly [[Volvo]] vehicles was phased out, with some retained for training and reserve purposes, and replaced between 2002 and 2011 with new [[Mercedes-Benz]] vehicles.\n\nIn 2012, the LFB purchased five [[Mini Countryman]]s for conversion into instant response vehicles. The two-seat cars are fitted with six extinguishers (two each of water, foam and powder), plus a first-aid kit and defibrillator, and may be deployed to investigate automatic alarms actuating and smaller fires such as those in rubbish bins which do not require a full-sized engine and crew. The brigade has indicated a wish to add more smaller vehicles to its fleet, including [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover utility vehicles]] which could be fitted with water pumps, breathing apparatus and pull-out equipment drawers, and with enough space for four firefighters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/ingear/cars/article1218397.ece|title=Little squirts to the rescue&nbsp;\u2013 The Sunday Times|work=thesundaytimes.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221083538/http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/ingear/cars/article1218397.ece|archivedate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the LFB announced they would be replacing the older-generation (currently used) [[Mercedes-Benz Atego]] pump appliances with brand new Mercedes-Benz Ategos which include new features such as: an improved 'crew cab' for the comfort and safety of firefighters, new high-pressure hoses which can deliver twice as much water as previous models, a brand new electronically-controlled pump, and a more economical and environment-friendly EURO VI engine, which will be compatible with London's low-emission zones. In 2017, 52 initial appliance orders are being rolled out across London ready for operational use, replacing the older 2002-2004 pumps, and later replacing the newer 2006-2008 pumps. The primary reason for the replacement of the older Ategos was due to their age (some being 15 years old) and poor economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_New-Brigade-vehicle-prototype-gets-royal-approval.asp#.WH582H2DHIU|title=News|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101113950/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/LatestNewsReleases_New-Brigade-vehicle-prototype-gets-royal-approval.asp#.WH582H2DHIU|archivedate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, the LFB's frontline operational fleet consists of:\n* Approximately 100 Dual Pump Ladders (DPL) (plus approximately 25 used for training)\n* Approximately 50 Pumps (P)\n* 15 Fire Rescue Units (FRU) (plus 1 for training)\n* 14 [[Urban Search and Rescue]] (USAR) multi-purpose vehicles\n* 8 Incident Response Units (IRU)\n* 8 Command Support Units (CSU)\n* 7 Aerial Ladder Platforms (ALP)\n* 6 Operational Support Units (OSU)\n* 6 High-volume Pumps (HVP)\n* 6 Fire Investigation Units (FIU)\n* 5 Instant Response Vehicles (IRV)\n* 4 Turntable Ladders (TL)\n* 4 Hose Laying Units (HLU)\n* 3 Bulk Foam Units (BFU)\n* 2 Scientific Support Units (SSU)\n* 2 Detection, Identification, and Monitoring Units (DIM)\n* 1 All-terrain Pump\n* 1 Heavy Distribution Unit (HDU)\n* 1 Fire Investigation Dog Unit (FID)\n* 1 Fireboat (plus 1 used as a reserve and for training)\n\n=== Improvements ===\nThe programme of improvements in staffing and equipment undertaken by the LFB since the [[September 11 attacks]] to improve London's resilience and its capability to deal with major emergencies, including the threat of terrorism has included: ten Incident Response Units; two Scientific Support Units; four different types of [[urban search and rescue]] (USAR) vehicles and ten USAR personnel carriers; three mass decontamination resilience units; and six equipment carriers known as Operational Support Units.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=893 Better preparation for major emergencies and terrorist attacks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010025037/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=893 |date=10 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nArchitecturally, fire stations vary in age and design from [[Edwardian era]] red-brick fire houses to modern spacious blocks complete with additional specialist facilities.<ref>[http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=20 Firefleet.co.uk gallery of London fire stations] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030939/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=20 |date=28 September 2007 }}</ref> Early fire stations were originally built with horse-drawn appliances in mind and with traditional features such as the [[fireman's pole]], used by firefighters to gain rapid access from their upstairs quarters to the fire engine garages below when summoned.\n\nMore modern fire stations, though constructed without such features, often have more spacious accommodation and facilities for staff of both sexes, public visitor areas such as community safety offices and other amenities. An example of these is the new fire station in [[Hammersmith]] which opened in 2003,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2977963.stm New \u00a37.7m fire station at Hammersmith] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209213057/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2977963.stm |date=9 February 2008 }}, 2003</ref> just a few hundred yards along Shepherd's Bush Road from the previous local fire station which had been constructed in 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hammersmithtoday.co.uk/default.asp?section=info&page=oldfirestation.htm|title=Hammersmith Old Fire Station Set to be a Pub|work=hammersmithtoday.co.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929152752/http://www.hammersmithtoday.co.uk/default.asp?section=info&page=oldfirestation.htm|archivedate=29 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Modernisation ===\n\nIn 2008, existing LFB facilities were deemed unsuitable to meet the demands of modern firefighting and training. The LFB has been training firefighters at its current Grade 2 [[listed building]] in Southwark since 1878.<ref name=\"Training P.31\">\"LFB works with Babcock to deliver change to firefighter training\" ''Training''.  April/May 2012 MMC Publications. P.31</ref>\n\nIn response, the LFB signed a partnership contract with Babcock International Group PLC to provide firefighter training over the course of 25 years beginning in 2012.<ref name=\"Training P.31\" /> Babcock is also the number one training provider to the [[Royal Navy]], which includes firefighter training. The improvement program for firefighting training will introduce two new dedicated training centres and upgrades to 10 regional training centres. There will also be further improvements through additional computers and training facilities across many of the capital's 103 fire stations. The new firefighting training systems, supplied by [[Process Combustion Ltd]], will have low environmental impact and will allow firefighter training to take place at night under simulated extreme conditions that firefighters will face on incident ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.process-combustion.co.uk/firetraining/firetraining_overview.html |title=Fire Training Systems \u2013 Bespoke Fire Training System |work=Process Combustion |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712013452/http://www.process-combustion.co.uk/firetraining/firetraining_overview.html |archivedate=12 July 2012 }}</ref> In addition to improving training facilities, Babcock's proposals will increase the amount of time available for firefighter training and save the LFB an estimated \u00a366m over the next 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babcockinternational.com/media-centre/babcock-selected-as-preferred-bidder-for-london-fire-brigade-training/?alttemplate=MobileNewsItem |title=London Fire Brigade chooses Babcock to deliver biggest changes to firefighting training for 130 years |work=babcockinternational.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729024416/http://www.babcockinternational.com/media-centre/babcock-selected-as-preferred-bidder-for-london-fire-brigade-training/?alttemplate=MobileNewsItem |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n=== Fire station closures ===\n[[File:This fire station is now closed - Clerkenwell.jpg|thumb|Sign in the window of Clerkenwell fire station reads \"This fire station is now closed\".]]\nThe creation of the Greater London Council in 1965 saw the number of LFB stations increase. The LFB absorbed some stations from the county brigades. At the time there were a handful of smaller brigades: Middlesex, Croydon, West Ham and East Ham \u2013 they were all incorporated into the LFB.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp London Fire Brigade Key Dates (1965), (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618055617/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/about_us/our_history/key_dates.asp |date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> By 1965 the LFB had 115 stations, plus two river stations.\n\nThe LFB has an ongoing policy of upgrading existing fire stations, and building new stations to replace those that are no longer suitable for the requirements of a modern-day fire service.<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=793 LFB Press Release P039/06, 23 June 06, (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012062149/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/detail.asp?id=793 |date=12 October 2007 }}</ref> In February 2010, [[Boris Johnson]] officially opened the LFB's first new station in four years, at [[Harold Hill]]. The mayor hailed the station's exceptional environmental sustainability, calling it the \"greenest station in the capital\".<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1303.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Error Page<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006204951/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/NewsReleases2009_PR1303.asp |date=6 October 2010 }}</ref> In the past two decades the total number of stations has reduced slightly, with the following permanent closures, including 10 in January 2014 as part of budget cuts:\n* 2014: [[Belsize Park|Belsize]] (A42), [[Bow, London|Bow]] (F27), [[Clerkenwell]] (A27), [[Downham]] (E32), [[Dalston|Kingsland]] (F31), [[Knightsbridge]] (A26), [[Silvertown]] (F46), [[Southwark]] (E33), [[Westminster]] (A25), and [[Woolwich]] (E24).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london24.com/news/protests_at_london_fire_stations_over_closures_as_union_says_boris_johnson_has_blood_on_his_hands_1_3188492 |title=Protests at London fire stations over closures as union says Boris Johnson has \u2018blood on his hands\u2019 |work=London 24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109203045/http://www.london24.com/news/protests_at_london_fire_stations_over_closures_as_union_says_boris_johnson_has_blood_on_his_hands_1_3188492 |archivedate=9 January 2014 }}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Manchester Square]] (A22)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=157|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=157|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Manchester Square 1889 color fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1999: [[Barbican Estate|Barbican]] (A29)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=4|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=4|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Barbican fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1998: Heathrow Airport (new station subsequently opened when the central terminal area was re-classified as \"A\" risk)<ref>[http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/lfepa/reports/2005/fep778.pdf Heathrow Fire Station \u2013 Taking of new lease 15 Sep 05 (accessed 24 October 2007)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025155514/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/lfepa/reports/2005/fep778.pdf |date=25 October 2007 }}</ref>\n* 1998: [[Shooter's Hill]] (E26)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=218|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=218|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Shooters Hill 1912 fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 1993: [[Sanderstead]] (H30) (originally a Surrey Fire Brigade station)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=210|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070504164225/http://www.firefleet.co.uk/gallery/displayimage.php?album=20&pos=210|url-status=dead|title=Firefleet.co.uk - Stations/Sanderstead 1935 fire station|date=4 May 2007|archivedate=4 May 2007|website=firefleet.co.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Regional control centre ==\n{{Main|FiReControl}}\nIn October 2007, the Department for Communities and Local Government announced that the location for the new regional control centre, dedicated to the capital and part of the [[FiReControl]] project, would be at the Merton industrial estate in the [[London Borough of Merton]].<ref>Dept of Communities and Local Government: News Release 193, Site of  London's New Fire Control Centre Announced, 17 October 2007</ref> FiReControl was however scrapped in 2010.\n\n== Major or notable incidents ==\nThe geographical area covered by the LFB along with the major transport infrastructure and the political, business and administrative bases typical of a capital city has seen the brigade involved in many significant incidents.\n\n=== Major incident procedure ===\nA \"major incident\" is defined as any emergency that requires the implementation of special arrangements by one or more of London's emergency services and will generally include the involvement, either directly or indirectly, of large numbers of people.<ref name=MetMajorIncident>{{cite web|url=http://www.met.police.uk/leslp/docs/Major_incident_procedure_manual_7th_ed.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=29 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111182638/http://www.met.police.uk/leslp/docs/Major_incident_procedure_manual_7th_ed.pdf |archivedate=11 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAny member of any of the emergency services can initiate a major incident. Responsibility for the rescue of persons involved lies with the LFB. The care and transportation of casualties to hospital is the responsibility of the London Ambulance Service. Police will ease these operations by co-ordinating the emergency services, local authorities and other agencies.<ref name=MetMajorIncident />\n\nWhen a major incident is declared the services, along with civilian agencies, use a structural system known as [[Gold \u2013 silver \u2013 bronze command structure|gold-silver-bronze command]] that allows them to follow a set procedure for incident management.  Put simply, gold relates to strategic control of an incident, silver to tactical command, and bronze to operational control.  The term gold command can also relate to an emergency service building, mobile control unit or other base that becomes the focal point (often remotely) for the incident's management.<ref name=MetMajorIncident />\n\nAdditionally, a major incident can lead to the government activating its coordination facility, known as [[Cabinet Office Briefing Room|COBR]].\n\n=== Notable incidents ===\n<!-- This list is currently in descending chronological order. -->\nNotable incidents, some declared \"major incidents\" and some in which firefighters lost their lives, where the LFB has played a significant role include:\n* '''Grenfell Tower fire, 2017''' (40 pumps)\n[[File:Grenfell Tower fire.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in 2017]]\n: In June 2017 the LFB sent over 200 firefighters and officers in 40 fire engines, all 14 of its fire rescue units, four aerial ladder platforms and multiple command and operational support units to the [[Grenfell Tower fire]] in north Kensington. Crews were mobilised to the large tower block, which was ultimately almost completely alight, on the Lancaster West estate in the early hours of 14 June 2017 and some remained there for several days bringing the blaze under control. One of [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]]'s aerial ladder platforms was also requested due to its additional height. There were 72 fatalities making the incident Britain's deadliest residential fire since [[the Blitz]] during World War II.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_North-Kensington-tower-block-fire-Wednesday-14-June.asp|title=Incidents|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102183627/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_North-Kensington-tower-block-fire-Wednesday-14-June.asp|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Wembley industrial estate, 2017''' (20 pumps)\n: Over 120 firefighters, 20 pumps and four aerial ladder platforms were mobilised to a large fire in industrial units in Wembley in January 2017. The blaze affected a number of two-storey units and took around 17 hours to bring under control, and days to dampen down and declare the site safe. Crews from Wembley, Northolt, Willesden, Park Royal, Stanmore and Hillingdon fire stations attended the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_wembley-industrial-unit-fire.asp|title=Incidents|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531124922/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_wembley-industrial-unit-fire.asp|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Camden market fire, 2014''' (10 pumps)\n: Ten fire engines and over 70 firefighters and officers were called to a fire at Stables Market on Chalk Farm Road, [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]], in May 2014. A number of shops under railway arches were damaged by the blaze. Around 600 people were evacuated from the area. Crews were first mobilised at around 8 p.m. and the fire was under control by 10:50 p.m. Crews from Kentish Town, Euston, West Hampstead, Lambeth, Holloway, Islington and Soho stations attended the incident. Early indications suggested that the cause of the fire was an accidental electrical issue.\n* '''Vauxhall helicopter crash, 2013'''\n:Nearly 150 firefighters were involved in operations following [[Vauxhall helicopter crash|a helicopter crash]] in [[Vauxhall]] in misty conditions during the morning rush-hour on 16 January 2013. Several specialist vehicles, including heavy rescue and urban search and rescue, were mobilised to the scene where the wreckage fell onto a street, damaging five cars, two motorbikes and two adjacent buildings, after the aircraft's rotor blades struck a [[Crane (machine)|construction crane]] attached to [[St George Wharf Tower]]. The pilot and one person on the ground were killed in the incident. Fire crews also attended the tower block where the crane was left in a precarious position, and evacuated hundreds of workers and dozens of homes. A [[fireboat]] also carried out a precautionary search of the nearby [[River Thames]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_16Jan12R.asp|title=London Fire Brigade|date=27 October 2011|work=london-fire.gov.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119022842/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/LatestIncidentsContainer_16Jan12R.asp|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-21049125 | publisher=BBC News | title=London helicopter crash: Pilot's death 'devastating' | date=16 January 2013 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117040525/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-21049125 | archivedate=17 January 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Dagenham recycling centre fire, 2012''' (40 pumps)\n:Over 200 firefighters attended what was described by the commissioner as the largest fire in London \"for several years\". The LFB took just over four hours to bring under control the one-storey [[Dagenham]] recycling plant the size of a football pitch which was completely alight, sending a plume of smoke over east London. In addition to 40 fire engines, an aerial ladder platform, command unit, hose layer and three operational support vehicles attended.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19234182 | publisher=BBC News | title=Biggest fire 'for years' in Dagenham, London | date=12 August 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820000822/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19234182 | archivedate=20 August 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Camden Market fire, 2008''' (20 pumps)<ref name=journal>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2007/05/welcome.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052050/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2007/05/welcome.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n:Fire ravaged the stalls at the historic [[Camden Market]] in February 2008, forcing the evacuation of 450 people from the area, including 100 from their homes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1578257/Camden-Market-fire-damage-will-cost-millions.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Lewis | last=Carter | title=Camden Market fire damage 'will cost millions' | date=11 February 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914020436/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1578257/Camden-Market-fire-damage-will-cost-millions.html | archivedate=14 September 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Twenty fire engines and over 100 firefighters fought to bring the blaze under control within six hours and prevent any loss of life.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7237119.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Blaze ravages London market area | date=9 February 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215072250/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/7237119.stm | archivedate=15 February 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Cutty Sark fire, 2007''' (6 pumps)\n:Although no lives were endangered and a major incident was not initiated, the fire at the historic tea clipper ''[[Cutty Sark]]'' in May 2007 became a notable incident for the widespread interest of national media and the unusual circumstances \u2013 having been caused by an industrial vacuum cleaner inadvertently left switched on by renovation workers for 48 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6675381.stm|title=BBC NEWS \u2013 UK \u2013 England \u2013 London \u2013 Blaze ravages historic Cutty Sark|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523120139/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6675381.stm|archivedate=23 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3109243/Cutty-Sark-fire-Security-guards-put-their-feet-up-as-blaze-ravaged-ship.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Edwards | title=Cutty Sark fire: Security guards 'put their feet up' as blaze ravaged ship | date=30 September 2008 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201174318/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3109243/Cutty-Sark-fire-Security-guards-put-their-feet-up-as-blaze-ravaged-ship.html | archivedate=1 December 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Two fire appliances and an aerial appliance arrived at the scene within six minutes of the initial call to emergency services, and the commanding officer immediately requested an additional four appliances; firefighters brought the blaze under control within an hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/CuttySarkFireReport-29Sep08.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128063551/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/CuttySarkFireReport-29Sep08.pdf |archivedate=28 November 2011 }}</ref>\n* '''Oxford Street, 2007''' (30 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:From 27 to 28 April 2007 London's busiest shopping area was closed whilst more than 100 firefighters tackled a large fire in a flat above a department store on [[Oxford Street]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6597753.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Crews tackle Oxford Street fire | date=26 April 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901233125/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/6597753.stm | archivedate=1 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The clothing retailer [[New Look (clothing retailer)|New Look]] was later fined a record \u00a3400,000 for fire safety breaches.<ref>[http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23775110-new-look-fined-pound-40000-after-oxford-street-fire.do New Look fined \u014140,000 after Oxford Street fire | News<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109134638/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23775110-new-look-fined-pound-40000-after-oxford-street-fire.do |date=9 January 2011 }}</ref>\n[[File:Buncefield015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Buncefield fire]]]]\n* '''Buncefield oil terminal, 2005'''\n:The UK's [[Buncefield fire|largest peacetime fire]] broke out on 11 December 2005 at the [[Hertfordshire Oil Storage Terminal]] at Buncefield. Although the major incident was attended by the LFB, its role was assisting and providing additional foam supplies to the neighbouring [[Hertfordshire Fire and Rescue Service]], to the north of London, whose \"ground\" the incident took place in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/read_this/buncefield_explosions/|title=BBC \u2013 Beds Herts and Bucks \u2013 Read This \u2013 Depot explosion|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060715181824/http://www.bbc.co.uk/threecounties/read_this/buncefield_explosions/|archivedate=15 July 2006}}</ref>\n* '''7 July 2005 bombings''' (12/12/10 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:Multiple major incidents were declared across London in response to the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|7/7 terrorist attacks]]. A total of 34 pumps and nine fire-rescue units were mobilised to the four bomb sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_4942000/4942238.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 7 \u2013 2005: Bomb attacks on London|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610231301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/7/newsid_4942000/4942238.stm|archivedate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n* '''Bethnal Green Road, 2004''' (8 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:A fire in shops and flats in Bethnal Green Road, [[Bethnal Green]] in July 2004 gained coverage in the national media due to the deaths of two LFB firefighters. The first LFB fatalities since 1993 were two of the 50 mobilised to the scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3909269.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Two firefighters killed in blaze | date=20 July 2004 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519023800/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3909269.stm | archivedate=19 May 2006 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Buckingham Palace fire, 2002''' (20 pumps)<ref name=journal />\n:Fire broke out on 2 June 2002 in the west terrace of [[Buckingham Palace]]. At its peak, 20 fire engines and 100 firefighters were on the scene, and in the course of firefighting operations four people were rescued from the roof. The Royal Family were away at the time.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2022274.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Buckingham Palace blaze out | date=2 June 2002 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202132522/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2022274.stm | archivedate=2 February 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/jun/03/jubilee.monarchy2 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Rebecca | last1=Allison | first2=Tania | last2=Branigan | title=Thousands evacuated in fire | date=3 June 2002 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328011447/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/jun/03/jubilee.monarchy2 | archivedate=28 March 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Paddington train crash, 1999''' (12 pumps)\n:Also known as the [[Ladbroke Grove rail crash]], two trains collided a short distance outside of [[London Paddington station|Paddington station]] in October 1999, killing 31 people.<ref name=journal /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/5/newsid_2493000/2493593.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 5 \u2013 1999: Death toll rising in Paddington crash|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307125727/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/5/newsid_2493000/2493593.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Cannon Street train crash, 1991'''\n:Two people were killed and over 500 injured in the [[Cannon Street station rail crash]] in January 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 8 \u2013 1991: One dead as train crashes into buffers|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108160834/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/january/8/newsid_4091000/4091741.stm|archivedate=8 January 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Marchioness disaster, 1989'''\n:The [[Marchioness disaster]] of August 1989 involved a collision on the [[River Thames]] between a pleasure boat, the ''Marchioness'', and a gravel dredger, the ''Bowbelle'', resulting in the sinking of the ''Marchioness'' and the deaths of 51 people. Initial confusion over which bridge the ship had sunk near meant fireboats and fire engines were sent in the wrong direction. It was not until half an hour later that a station officer from Southwark radioed: \"''Marchioness'' sunk, believed downstream of Blackfrairs Bridge with unknown number of people in river and Met Police searching river between Blackfriars and Waterloo Bridges.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/20/newsid_2500000/2500211.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 20 \u2013 1989: Marchioness river crash 'kills 30'|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307113723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/august/20/newsid_2500000/2500211.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''Clapham Junction train crash, 1988'''\n:The [[Clapham Junction rail crash]] occurred on 12 December 1988 when a busy commuter train passed a defective signal and ran into the back of a second train, derailing it into the path of an oncoming third train. Thirty-five people died and 69 others suffered serious injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/12/newsid_2547000/2547561.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 12 \u2013 1988: 35 dead in Clapham rail collision|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307133743/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/december/12/newsid_2547000/2547561.stm|archivedate=7 March 2008}}</ref>\n* '''King's Cross fire, 1987'''\n:The [[King's Cross fire]] broke out on 18 November 1987 under a wooden [[escalator]] leading from one of the [[King's Cross St. Pancras tube station|King's Cross tube station]] platforms to the surface. The blaze and smoke claimed 31 lives, including that of Soho station officer Colin Townsley while he rescued a woman from a ticket office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/kings-cross-fire-1987.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708051619/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/kings-cross-fire-1987.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref> Investigation and research of the fire resulted in the discovery of the [[trench effect]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_2519000/2519675.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 18 \u2013 1987: King's Cross station fire 'kills 27'|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070627175401/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/november/18/newsid_2519000/2519675.stm|archivedate=27 June 2007}}</ref>\n* '''Hampton Court fire, 1986''' (20 pumps, jointly with Surrey)\n: On 31 March 1986, a fire broke out at [[Hampton Court Palace]], which killed one person. 20 fire engines and around 125 firefighters from both the LFB and the neighbouring [[Surrey Fire and Rescue Service]] were sent to the scene, which is on the border between the two areas. Firefighters played a major role in the rescue of some of the more valuable artworks from the palace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/surrey-news/hampton-court-palace-blaze-recalled-11131124|title=Hampton Court Palace blaze recalled 30 years on after fire ripped through historic building|work=Get Surrey|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n* '''New Cross house fire, 1981'''\n:The infamous [[New Cross house fire]] of 18 January 1981 claimed the lives of 13 people, all aged between 14 and 22, attending a birthday party.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3479827.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Eyewitnesses describe killer fire | date=11 February 2004 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040227141935/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3479827.stm | archivedate=27 February 2004 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The exact and true cause has never been established.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12182927 | publisher=BBC News | title=Did the New Cross fire create a black British identity? | date=18 January 2011 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121063429/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12182927 | archivedate=21 January 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Denmark Place fire, 1980'''\n:In the early hours of 15 August 1980, a man who was earlier ejected from an illegal drinking and gambling club in [[Soho]] returned with gasoline and started a fire that killed 37 people and injured 23 others. The incident became known as the [[Denmark Place fire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2010/01/soho-club-fire-1980.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052202/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2010/01/soho-club-fire-1980.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''The Granary warehouse, 1978''' (35 pumps, 6 turntable ladders)\n:1 October 1978 saw one of London's largest post\u2013[[World War II]] fires, at The Granary warehouse on St. Pancras Way. At the first call at 2:58 a.m., three fire engines and a turntable ladder were sent to the scene. The scale of the blaze is evidenced by the rapid development of the LFB's mobilisation: make pumps four at 3:05 a.m.; make pumps six at 3:07 a.m.; make pumps 10 at 3:12 a.m.; make pumps 15 and turntable ladders 2 at 3:19 a.m.; make turntable ladders 4 at 3:39 a.m.; make pumps 20 and turntable ladders 6 at 3:51 a.m.; make pumps 25 at 4:19 a.m.; make hose layers 2 at 4:30 a.m.; and make pumps 35 at 5:13 a.m. At 4:50 a.m., the structure suffered a major collapse, killing firefighter Stephen Neill from Barbican station, seriously injuring three others, and destroying two fire engines.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Moorgate train crash, 1975'''\n:The [[Moorgate tube crash]] was a disaster on the London Underground in February 1975 when a train failed to stop and crashed into the [[Buffer stop|buffers]] at the end of a tunnel. The driver and 42 passengers were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/february/28/newsid_4298000/4298307.stm|title=BBC ON THIS DAY \u2013 28 \u2013 1975: Horror underground|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620042156/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/witness/february/28/newsid_4298000/4298307.stm|archivedate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Worsley Hotel fire, 1974''' (30 pumps)\n:The [[Worsley Hotel fire]] of December 1974 was an arson attack that killed seven people, including probationary firefighter Hamish Petit of Paddington station. Four fire engines, a turntable ladder and emergency tender were initially mobilised to the scene, gradually increased to 30 pumps with three turntable ladders, three emergency tenders, and hose layers. A 41-year-old kitchen porter was convicted of the attack and seven counts of manslaughter and was jailed for life.<ref name=journal /><ref name=LineOfDuty>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/11/bethnal-green-2004.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052132/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/11/bethnal-green-2004.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''1970s\u20131990s IRA bombing campaign'''\n:During the [[Provisional IRA campaign 1969\u20131997|1970s\u20131990s IRA bombing campaign]] throughout the last quarter of the 20th century, several major bombings were carried out in London by the [[Provisional IRA]], including at the [[Palace of Westminster]], [[Tower of London]], and [[Harrods]]. A list of these and other bombings in London to which the LFB responded can be found [[London bombings|here]].\n* '''Dudgeons Wharf, 1969'''\n:[[J & W Dudgeon|Dudgeons Wharf]] on the [[Isle of Dogs]] contained a site of over 100 tanks of various capacities up to 20,000 gallons<ref>{{cite news | title = 5 firemen killed in explosion |newspaper = The Times | date = 18 July 1969 | page = 1|issue=57615 }}</ref> used for storing oils and spirits. A fire started when workmen were cutting up old oil tanks. The LFB was called \u2013 six pumps, a foam tender and the fireboat ''[[Massey Shaw]]'' \u2013 and while firefighters tackled the fire an oil tank exploded. Five firefighters from Millwall and Poplar stations were killed, the largest single loss of life in the LFB since the Second World War.<ref name=LineOfDuty /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firehouse.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-92474.html|title=The Dudgeons Wharf Explosion.... 17th July 1969|work=Firehouse|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928115304/http://www.firehouse.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-92474.html|archivedate=28 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568275/The-toll-of-duty.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Richard | last=Gray | title=The toll of duty | date=4 November 2007 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113140958/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1568275/The-toll-of-duty.html | archivedate=13 January 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* '''Bishopsgate goods yard, 1964''' (40 pumps, 12 turntable ladders)\n:London's main railway goods terminal at {{rws|Bishopsgate}} was gutted by a spectacular fire in December 1964. Within 37 minutes of the first crews arriving on scene, the scale of the blaze was so intense and widespread that 40 fire engines had been mobilised. In addition, 12 turntable ladders, two hose layers, two emergency tenders, and 235 firefighters battled the fire which killed two customs officials and destroyed hundreds of railway wagons, dozens of motor vehicles and millions of pounds worth of goods. The site remained derelict for the next 30 years until being rebuilt as [[Shoreditch High Street railway station]].<ref name=journal /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fireservice.co.uk/history-articles/bishopsgate|title=Bishopsgate Goods Depot|work=fireservice.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110127132143/http://www.fireservice.co.uk/history-articles/bishopsgate|archivedate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Smithfield market, 1958''' (50 pumps)\n:Over the course of firefighting operations at London's central meat market in January 1958, a total of 389 fire engines with more than 1,700 firefighters from 58 fire stations worked in shifts to tackle a fire of exceptional proportions.<ref name=journal />\n:After the initial call, the LFB mobilised three pumps, a turntable ladder and emergency tender at 2:18 a.m. Upon arrival, a station officer and firefighter from Clerkenwell station headed down into the basement where it was apparent a major fire had broken out. Both became trapped in the basement cellars and suffocated to death. Excessive heat, dense smoke and worsening conditions meant crews had to be rotated as frequently as every 15 minutes, as firefighters suffered from severe heat exhaustion.\n:Twenty-four hours later, with 800 oxygen cylinders used, the fire in the basement suddenly broke up into the first floor of the market, with flames seeping 100&nbsp;ft in the air, engulfing the entire market. The fire, although brought under control and reduced, was not fully extinguished for two weeks. Valuable lessons were learnt after the Smithfield blaze, including introducing a tally system of firefighters' locations and quantity of breathing apparatus.\n:On the 50th anniversary of the Smithfield blaze, in 2008, the then Deputy Commissioner of the LFB said: \"This was a landmark fire in the history of London and its fire brigade. It is important that we remember this tragic fire and honour the memory of the two London firefighters who lost their lives.\"<ref name=\"londonfirejournal.blogspot.com\">{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/smithfield-market-1958.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708051647/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005/07/smithfield-market-1958.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n* '''Covent Garden warehouse fire, 1954'''\n:While fighting a fire in a five-storey warehouse adjacent to [[Covent Garden]], a station officer and firefighter, both of Clerkenwell station, were killed. Six more were hospitalised, with three requiring plastic surgery treatment.<ref name=\"londonfirejournal.blogspot.com\" />\n* '''London Blitz'''\n:On 7 September 1940, a sub-officer at West Ham fire station witnessed the start of [[the Blitz]] by Nazi Germany on London. He reported that three miles of waterfront buildings had become a continuous blaze, and ordered 500 fire engines to be mobilised. The commander thought this an exaggeration and sent someone to investigate the situation, who reported back that 1,000 were required. More than 300 firefighters perished in the widespread and sustained bombing campaign, including two in a direct hit on Soho fire station and six in a direct hit on Wandsworth fire station.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Crystal Palace fire, 1936''' (88 pumps)\n:A major fire which led to the complete [[The Crystal Palace#Destruction by fire|destruction of the Crystal Palace]] on 30 November 1936 was attended by 88 fire engines and 438 firefighters from the London Fire Brigade and three other brigades, plus 749 police officers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2007/05/21/fire_destroyed_feature.shtml|title=Crystal Palace|work=BBC News|date=24 October 2014|access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Colonial Wharf, 1935''' (60 pumps)\n:An eight-storey rubber warehouse in Wapping High Street burned for four days from 27 September 1935, with 60 fire engines in attendance. It was the first major incident for one of the LFB's most famous fireboats, the ''[[Massey Shaw]]'', which greatly assisted land crews, who were hampered by inaccessibility, by supplying a vast water jet to allow the land crews to regroup and prevent the fire from spreading to adjoining warehouses.<ref name=journal />\n* '''Vauxhall, 1918'''\n:A fire on 30 January 1918 claimed the lives of seven London firefighters.<ref name=journal /> Staff at Vauxhall fire station were alerted to the incident by a passer-by, and upon arrival found a three-storey private house well alight, with the roof and upper floor partially collapsed. The fire was extinguished within two hours but firefighters remained in the building dampening down. It was then, while the men were on the ground floor, that the building suffered a total structural collapse. Six firefighters died on scene, one later from severe injury, and two suffered lesser injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005_11_01_archive.html|title=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|author=LONDON FIRE JOURNAL|work=londonfirejournal.blogspot.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708052248/http://londonfirejournal.blogspot.com/2005_11_01_archive.html|archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable exercises ===\n{{Expand list|date=July 2016}}\n* '''[[Exercise Unified Response]], 2016'''\n:London Fire Brigade led the planning and staging of a large, multi-agency exercise at multiple sites in London, simulating the collapse of Waterloo station onto an underground train.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/exercise-unified-response.asp |title=Exercise Unified Response |accessdate=18 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727031111/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/exercise-unified-response.asp |archivedate=27 July 2016  }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n*'''''London's Firefighters''''': Edited by David C Pike and published by [[Austin Macauley Publishers]] ({{ISBN|978-1-78455-541-2}}) in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinmacauley.com/|title=Austin Macauley Publishers -- Books, eBooks & audiobooks|website=www.austinmacauley.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321133515/http://austinmacauley.com/|archivedate=21 March 2018}}</ref> A wonderfully readable, lavishly illustrated anthology of articles, fiction and verse about the London Fire Brigade, much of it drawn from the award-winning in-house magazine 'London Fireman' (1966\u201382) and 'London Firefighter' (1982\u20132005). The book celebrates the forthcoming 150th anniversary of London's fire brigade's (1866\u20132016) by delivering both a comprehensive history of the London Fire Brigade and provides a fascinating portrait of individual firemen and firewomen at work and (occasionally) at play. The numerous, often highly dramatic illustrations, many from the London Fire Brigade and the Mary Evans Picture Library <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maryevans.com/|title=Mary Evans Picture Library. Historical images. Historical archive. Images of history. Images. Pictures. History. ILN. Stock. Photos Fine Art. Illustrations.|first=Mary Evans Picture Library, London|last=(http://www.maryevans.com)|website=www.maryevans.com|accessdate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208022252/http://www.maryevans.com/|archivedate=8 December 2017}}</ref> offer a lively commentary on the text.\n* '''''Beyond the Flames''''': Written by David C Pike and published by Austin Macauley Publishers ({{ISBN|978-1-84963-396-3}}) in 2013.<ref>[http://www.austinmacauley.com/authors_info.php?manufacturers_id=368 ''David C. Pike''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826090947/http://www.austinmacauley.com/authors_info.php?manufacturers_id=368 |date=26 August 2014 }}, Austin Macauley Publishers Ltd, 2014</ref> It is a personal, insider's account of the life and history of the London Fire Brigade from 1965 to the late 1990s. This book was runner-up in the 2014 [[The People's Book Prize (UK)]] (the UK's prestigious first-time author literary award) and was nominated for the Beryl Bainbridge Award 2014. In 2015 Beyond the Flames was a finalist in the (Wishing Shelf Independent Books Awards). David Pike was awarded the [[Queen's Commendation for Brave Conduct]], and went on to rise to senior rank and organised many of the Brigade's most high-profile events in the early 1990s.\n* '''''Fire Wars:''''' In July 2003, the BBC followed the arson investigators of the LFB's fire investigation unit. The two-part series looked at how the LFB investigated \"4,000 fires where the cause was unknown\". The second programme, ''Fire Wars: Murder Most Foul'', centred on one investigation.<ref>Fire Wars, Produced by Folio/Mentorn for BBC Television transmitted on 1 July 2003 & 8 July 2003</ref>\n* '''''London's Burning:''''' The [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] television series ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'' was based on the fictional Blackwall fire station and centred on characters of the station's blue watch. It was originally a 1986 television film, written by [[Jack Rosenthal]]. The fire station used as the principal location in the drama was Dockhead, near [[London Bridge]], before moving to Leyton fire station in east London late in the series.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0095537/ London's Burning: The Movie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050305180838/http://imdb.com/title/tt0095537/ |date=5 March 2005 }}, (IMDB)</ref> The series that followed the film ran from 1988 to 2002.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0123355/ \"London's Burning\" TV series] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913194515/http://imdb.com/title/tt0123355/ |date=13 September 2007 }}, (IMDB)</ref>\n* '''''Fire!:''''' The LFB's Kingsland Road fire station in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], east London, was the focus of a documentary series by [[Thames Television]] for ITV, broadcast in the spring of 1991.<ref>Fire! Produced & directed by Chris Oxley/Laurel Productions for Thames Television/ITV transmitted in 1991</ref> The documentary brought about an internal inquiry by the LFB after scenes were shown of firefighters having a food fight at a Christmas party in one of the programmes. Several watch members from Kingsland Road were suspended after the programme was broadcast on 27 June 1991.<ref>Ban on Party Firemen, Another TV Row, Pub Daily Mail, 28 June 1991</ref>\n* '''''Fireman! A Personal Account:''''' Former London firefighter [[Neil Wallington]] wrote an account of his experience in the LFB called ''Fireman! A Personal Account'', published in 1979.<ref name=\"wallington\" /> He chronicled his transition from a firefighter in the Croydon Fire Brigade through to his reaching the rank of station officer in the LFB.  He went on to become the Chief Fire Officer of the Devon fire brigade (now known as [[Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service]]) and has written several books about fire services over the world. Wallington's work outlined the change in working conditions in the LFB in the 1970s, a time that saw the working hours of firefighters reduced and conditions improved.\n* '''''Red Watch:''''' The former [[ITN]] newsreader [[Gordon Honeycombe]] became friendly with Neil Wallington while he was a station officer at [[Paddington]] fire station. In 1976, Honeycombe published  an account of the [[Worsley Hotel fire]], a major fire at a hostel in [[Maida Vale]] in 1974 that claimed the lives of seven people including one firefighter. The resulting book was called ''Red Watch'';<ref>Red Watch: The best seller about a fire and the men who fought it, by Gordon Honeycombe, Pub Arrow, 17 May 1976, {{ISBN|0-09-126310-7}}</ref> it provided a graphic account of a single incident, and outlined some of the changes to working practices that resulted from it.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Cyril Demarne]]\n* [[Fire Service College]]\n* [[FireLink]]\n* [[List of fire departments]]\n* [[List of British firefighters killed in the line of duty]]\n* [[London Air Ambulance]]\n* [[London Fire Brigade equipment]]\n* [[London Salvage Corps]]\n* [[Metropolitan Police Service]]\n* [[National Fire Savers Credit Union]]\n* [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/ London Fire Brigade]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090808003905/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/Stationsandlocations.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Find your local fire station]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130412082906/http://www.london-fire.gov.uk/WomenInTheBrigade.asp London Fire Brigade \u2013 Women in the Brigad]\n* [http://www.communities.gov.uk/fire/ Dept for Communities and Local Govt: Fire]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060901012330/http://www.opsi.gov.uk/acts.htm Cabinet Office: Acts of the UK Parliament]\n* [http://www.fbu.org.uk/index.php Fire Brigades Union]\n{{UK fire service}}\n<!---Headquarters building--->\n\n{{Coord|51.50335|-0.09862|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1865 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Fire and rescue services of England]]\n[[Category:Local government in London]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in London]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1865]]\n", "name_user": "Daask", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkstatutory authorityusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Fire_Brigade"}
{"title_page": "Viggo Johansen (journalist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian television presenter}}\n'''Viggo Johansen''' (born 19 August 1949) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] television presenter.\n\nHe has been a newspaper journalist in ''[[Dagbladet]]'' and worked for [[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]], but is best known from the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Viggo Johansen \u2013 kringkastingsmedarbeider|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=|location=|url=http://snl.no/Viggo_Johansen%2Fkringkastingsmedarbeider|language=Norwegian|accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe served as their correspondent in Brussels from 1993 to 1997, before he was appointed as magazine editor in 1998, news editor (among others of ''[[Dagsrevyen]]'') in 1999 and finance editor in 2001. From 2002 to 2009 he presented his own programme, ''[[Redaksjon 1]]''.<ref name=snl/> He continued with his own Saturday night show, ''Viggo p\u00e5 l\u00f8rdag''.<ref>{{cite news|title=NRK skal finne nytt humortalent|agency=Norwegian News Agency|date=26 August 2009|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s he played football for [[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball|V\u00e5lerengen]].<ref name=snl/> His son [[Victor Johansen]] became a professional footballer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box |before= |title=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] correspondent in Brussels|years=1993&ndash;1997|after= }}\n{{succession box |before=[[Hans-Wilhelm Steinfeld]] |title=Editor of ''[[Dagsrevyen]]''|years=1999&ndash;2001 |after=[[Annette Groth (journalist)|Annette Groth]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johansen, Viggo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian journalists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:V\u00e5lerenga Fotball players]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Norway-journalist-stub}}\n{{Norway-tv-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Viggo Johansen''' (born 19 August 1949) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] television presenter.\n\nHe has been a newspaper journalist in ''[[Dagbladet]]'' and worked for [[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]], but is best known from the [[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Viggo Johansen \u2013 kringkastingsmedarbeider|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=|location=|url=http://snl.no/Viggo_Johansen%2Fkringkastingsmedarbeider|language=Norwegian|accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe served as their correspondent in Brussels from 1993 to 1997, before he was appointed as magazine editor in 1998, news editor (among others of ''[[Dagsrevyen]]'') in 1999 and finance editor in 2001. From 2002 to 2009 he presented his own programme, ''[[Redaksjon 1]]''.<ref name=snl/> He continued with his own Saturday night show, ''Viggo p\u00e5 l\u00f8rdag''.<ref>{{cite news|title=NRK skal finne nytt humortalent|agency=Norwegian News Agency|date=26 August 2009|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s he played football for [[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball|V\u00e5lerengen]].<ref name=snl/> His son [[Victor Johansen]] became a professional footballer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box |before= |title=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation]] correspondent in Brussels|years=1993&ndash;1997|after= }}\n{{succession box |before=[[Hans-Wilhelm Steinfeld]] |title=Editor of ''[[Dagsrevyen]]''|years=1999&ndash;2001 |after=[[Annette Groth (journalist)|Annette Groth]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johansen, Viggo}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian journalists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:V\u00e5lerenga Fotball players]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Norway-journalist-stub}}\n{{Norway-tv-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Norwegian television presenter\", overriding Wikidata description \"Norwegian television presenter\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viggo_Johansen_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "WWCD (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = WWCD\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Griselda Records|Griselda]]\n| cover        = Griselda - WWCD.png\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2019|11|29}}\n| genre        = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length       = 46:27\n| label        = {{hlist|Griselda|[[Shady Records|Shady]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|Beat Butcha|Daringer|[[Eminem]]}}\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n| name        = WWCD\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = Dr. Bird's\n| single1date = October 18, 2019\n| single2     = Chef Dreds\n| single2date = November 8, 2019\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Earmilk]]''\n| rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://earmilk.com/album-reviews/664650/griselda/wwcd/|title=Album Review: Griselda - WWCD|last=Camaj|first=Margarit\u00eb \"Magi\"|date=December 3, 2019|website=[[Earmilk]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev2score = 4.5/5<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3583/title.review-griseldas-wwcd-is-harder-than-concrete-wrapped-in-iron-minus-the-eminem-feature|title=Review: Griselda's \"WWCD\" Is Harder Than Concrete Wrapped In Iron \u2014 Minus The Eminem Feature|last=Wallace|first=Riley|date=December 4, 2019|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev3score = 7.7/10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/griselda-wwcd/|title=Griselda: WWCD|last=Rytlewski|first=Evan|date=December 4, 2019|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Needle Drop]]''\n| rev4score = 7/10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theneedledrop.com/articles/2019/12/griselda-wwcd|title=Griselda - WWCD|last=Fantano|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Fantano|date=December 9, 2019|website=[[The Needle Drop]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''WWCD''''' (an [[initialism]] for '''''What Would Chine Gun Do''''') is the debut studio album by Griselda (rappers [[Westside Gunn]], [[Conway the Machine]], [[Benny the Butcher]] and producer Daringer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.53590/title.griselda-records-unveils-wwcd-tracklist-featuring-eminem-50-cent-raekwon-more|title=Griselda Records Drops Shady Records Debut 'WWCD'|last=Ivey|first=Justin|date=November 28, 2019|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=November 29, 2019}}</ref> It was released on November 29, 2019 via Griselda Records and [[Shady Records]]. The album is entirely produced by Daringer and Beat Butcha, and features [[guest appearance]]s from [[50 Cent]], [[Eminem]], Keisha Plum, Novel, [[Raekwon]] and Tiona Deniece. \n\nThe album was named after the late rapper Marchello \"Machine Gun Black\" Lowery a.k.a. Chine Gun, Benny\u2019s half-brother as well as Westside and Conway\u2019s first cousin who was murdered in [[Buffalo, New York]]. \n\nIts lead [[Single (music)|single]] \"Dr. Bird's\" was released on October 18, 2019. The second single, \"Chef Dreds\", was released on November 8, 2019.\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! List\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''Ambrosia For Heads''\n| Top 15 Hip-Hop Albums Of 2019 List\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ambrosiaforheads.com/2019/12/best-hiphop-albums-2019/|title=Ambrosia For Heads\u2019 Top 15 Hip-Hop Albums Of 2019 List|last=Commandeur|first=Jordan|date=December 18, 2019|website=Ambrosia For Heads|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n| Best Albums of 2019\n| {{center|22}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-2019/griselda-what-would-chine-do|title=The Best Albums of 2019|last=Diaz|first=Angel|website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| The Best Rap & Hip Hop Albums Of 2019\n| {{center|4}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/editorials/id.4393/title.the-best-rap-hip-hop-albums-of-2019|title=The Best Rap & Hip Hop Albums Of 2019|last=Wallace|first=Riley|website=[[HipHopDX]]|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs produced by Daringer and Beat Butcha, and written by Griselda, unless stated. Credits adapted from [[Apple Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/wwcd/1488564337|title=Wwcd by Griselda|website=[[Apple Music]]|access-date=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://istandardproducers.com/griselda-records-w-w-c-d-credits-and-streams/|title=Griselda \u2013 W.W.C.D. Credits|publisher=istandardproducers.com|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 46:27\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1  = Marchello Intro\n| note1   = featuring [[Raekwon]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Benny the Butcher|Jeremie Pennick]]|[[Conway the Machine|Demond Price]]|[[Westside Gunn|Alvin Worthy]]|[[Raekwon|Corey Woods]]|Eliot Dubock|Thomas Paldino}}\n| length1 = 2:11\n\n| title2 = Chef Dreds\n| length2 = 2:48\n| title3 = Moselle\n| length3 = 3:59\n| title4 = Cruiser Weight Coke\n| length4 = 3:52\n| title5 = Freddie HotSpot\n| length5 = 3:52\n| title6 = Dr. Bird\u2019s\n| length6 = 4:52\n\n| title7  = The Old Groove\n| note7   = featuring NOVEL\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Pennick|Price|Worthy|Dubock|Paldino|Alonzo Stevenson}}\n| length7 = 6:56\n\n| title8 = Scotties\n| length8 = 2:31\n\n| title9  = Kennedy\n| note9   = featuring Tiona Deniece\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Pennick|Price|Worthy|Dubock|Paldino|Tiona Deniece}}\n| length9 = 0:42\n\n| title10  = City on the Map\n| note10